<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will kick off a
three-day meeting here Friday on the future status of Jerusalem,
within the framework of an overall solution to the Arab-Israeli
problem.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said the two sides are expected to deal with
issues concerning the future status of Jerusalem, expressing "their
interests, fears and anxieties" over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Each side will send seven to eight representatives who are "very
close to leadership" to the meetings, including diplomats,
officials dealing with security matters and experts. (Cyprus-
Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres,
a Nobel Peace Prize Laureate, was unanimously confirmed on Friday
as the candidate for his Labor party to run for president.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of the 76-year-old former prime minister was
finally approved by the party's central committee, which held an
extraordinary party congress for the purpose. (Israel-President-
Candidate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Friday that
80 percent of Jewish settlements on the West Bank will be
maintained under Israeli sovereignty under whatever peace deal to
be reached between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the a meeting of the Labor Party's Central Committee
in Tel Aviv that some breakthroughs are in sight in the Israeli-
Palestinian negotiations. But no matter what will come out, 80
percent of the Jewish settlements will remain under Israeli
control. (Israel-Settlements-Peace Process)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss announced Friday at
his office that his government will increase the number of security
forces deployed in south Lebanon to 1,000, the local radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said in his declaration that Lebanon will deploy security
forces instead of the Lebanese army in south because "we now do not
want to serve as Israeli border guard in the liberated region".
(Lebanon-Security Forces-Deployment) 
</P>
</TEXT>
