<HEADLINE> U.N. to Probe Illegal Exploitation of Minerals in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday decided to set up a panel of independent experts to examine
how the war in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is financed
by illegal trading in minerals.
</P>
<P>
A presidential statement, issued at the end of a closed-door
meeting of the 15-nation Council which sent a delegation of seven
ambassadors to the region last month, asked U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan to appoint five experts for an initial period of six
months.
</P>
<P>
The panel, to be based in Nairobi which is the headquarters of
the U.N. operations in Africa, was asked to make a preliminary
report after three months. The move was intended to assess the
situation in a country where it has already authorized the
peacekeeping force of 5,500 troops and military observers.
</P>
<P>
The decision to look into illegal trade in mineral resources in
DRC is modeled upon the council's investigation of breaches of U.N.
sanctions against the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The DRC panel will "follow up on reports and collect
information on all activities of illegal exploitation of natural
resources and other forms of wealth," the statement said, adding
that it would "research and analyze the links between the
exploitation of natural resources and other forms of wealth in DRC
and the continuation of the conflict."
</P>
<P>
DRC, the former Zaire, is rich in copper, zinc, manganese, tin
and gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
