<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Reactivates Foreign Investment Inflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 2 (Xinhua) --  Colombian government announced
Friday a new regulation that eliminates red tape and eases
official control of foreign capital, to reactivate foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Colombia last year reached 4.020 billion
dollars, falling by 39 percent drop, according to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The reform, approved by the Economic and Social Policy National
Council (CONPES), to be promulgated in a short term by the
presidency, puts on an equal foot national and international
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the resources from abroad can arrive and start
operating immediately with the sole notification to the government
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The only restrictions are those related to the sectors of
defense, security, and handling of toxic wastes, for national
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Colombian investments abroad were also liberated, although with
limitations in tax and rates of exchange matters. The Bank of the
Republic (the government emitting bank), will be in both cases the
highest controlling authority.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Colombia, up to now and by region of
origin, is as follows: Central America, 38 percent; Europe, 28.2
percent; North America, 28.1 percent; South America, 4.4 percent,
and Asia, 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The composition of foreign investment in the country is as
follows:
financial sector, 32 percent; manufacturing industry, 28.7
percent; mines and coal, 20.6 percent; electricity, gas and water,
19.9 percent; restaurants and hotels, 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 foreign investment drop is attributed to the Brazilian
economic crisis and to the escalation of violence in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
