<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain: Fiji May Face Commonwealth Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain said Friday that Fiji might
be suspended from the Commonwealth if its new rulers do not return
the country to democratic constitutional government.
</P>
<P>
John Battle, a Foreign Office minister of state, said
suspension was a real option when Commonwealth foreign ministers
meet in London next week to discuss the crisis in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
But he said it was too early yet to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
Battle made the remarks after George Speight, the leader of the
coup in Fiji, told the BBC in an interview that he would free the
hostages over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever way Fiji comes through this, then if it turns its
back on democracy, then there are a range of options," Battle told
BBC radio's Today program.
</P>
<P>
When asked if suspension from the Commonwealth was one of the
options, Battle said it "really is a serious option if Fijians
were to find themselves in this position."
</P>
<P>
"But what we have to do is not make judgments now, because it's
still unclear," the minister of state said.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see respect for the democratic process, democratic
rights," Battle said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Fiji was suspended from the Commonwealth, which
mainly groups Britain and its former colonies, in 1987 after a
coup and was only allowed back in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
