<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Donates $3.1 Million to Ethiopian Immunization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan has donated 3.1 million
U.S. dollars to Ethiopia through the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) for the national polio and measles immunization
campaign this year.
</P>
<P>
The grant agreement was signed here by Japanese Ambassador to
Ethiopia Takehisa Nogami and UNICEF country representative Ibrahim
Jabr on Thursday, Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The fund covering 28 percent of the cost of the national
immunization scheduled for November and December would be used to
purchase vaccines against polio and measles as well as vitamin A
supplements.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's immunization campaign has shown encouraging results
with a significant reduction of both measles and polio in under
five age group, Nogami said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ibrahim Jabr, the immunization campaign against
preventable disease has reached 80 percent of the population
compared to 10 percent 30 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
