<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Boost Manufacturing Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
said Friday that his government would inject money in the
fledging manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
The President made the remarks when he officially opened the
43rd Copperbelt Mining, Agricultural and Commercial Show in Kitwe,
Copperbelt Province.
</P>
<P>
"I'm aware of the problems affecting the manufacturing industry
 especially with regard to investing capital. My government has
put in place plans aimed at revitalizing the Development Bank of
Zambia by providing it with required capital for medium and long
term lending to boost the productive capacity of our companies and
revitalizing the manufacturing industry," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
The President expressed concern at the depreciation of the
kwacha against main hard currencies, saying this has impacted
negatively on the industrial performance.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the privatization of copper mines would help
stabilize the national currency.
</P>
<P>
The President reassured foreign investors that their assets are
safe in Zambia and that they will not be nationalized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
