<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Vice President Warns against Environment Degradation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President Omar
Ali Juma on Friday called for joint efforts to contain the
alarming environmental degradation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony here to inaugurate the new board of the
Tanzanian National Environmental Management Council (NEMC), the
vice president said if the situation is left to continue, the
country will plunge into serious poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Incidents of water sources pollution, dynamite fishing, bush
fires and carelessly felling of trees, air pollution are rampant
in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Juma said the government will strive to secure funds to enable
NEMC execute its duties promptly because environment is synonymous
to development.
</P>
<P>
NEMC was established 17 years ago with a task of preparing
programs and guidelines on environmental management for
sustainable development in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The vice president commended the council for its exemplary work
in creating environmental awareness among the people.
</P>
<P>
He urged the council to set some environmental standards for
monitoring environmental abuse and assessing environmental impacts
of projects brought by investors.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is facing a series of environmental problems like
desertification, loss of wildlife habitat and deterioration of
aquatic ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists say increasing population pressure, felling
of wood for charcoal, fires and development of industries have
made the country lose 300,000 to 400,000 hectares of forests a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
