<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Nations Calls off Visit by Senior Official to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Friday called off a visit to Zimbabwe by a senior U.N.
official after the African nation said that it would seize 804
white-owned farms without compensation.
</P>
<P>
The Administrator of the U.N. Development Program (UNDP), Mark
Malloch Brown, had been due to visit Zimbabwe this weekend to
reactivate a two-year-old UNDP-sponsored land reform program in
the hope of ending the crisis over land ownership.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued here by Annan's spokesman, said, "Earlier
today, the Government of Zimbabwe publicly gave notice of its
intention to compulsorily acquire 804 farms from the large-scale
commercial farming sector. The Secretary-General regrets this
development because it undermines the ability of UNDP to build
international support, including resources, for a legally-based
solution, including compensation based on the principles of the
1998 land reform conference."
</P>
<P>
"In light of this announcement, whose consequences we will
need carefully to review, the Secretary-General has decided to
postpone the visit to Zimbabwe" by Brown, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General remains convinced, however, the issue
of land acquisition, redistribution and resettlement will not be
resolved without good faith efforts by all parties to achieve a
mutually agreed way forward," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Achieving a just and equitable solution is critical for the
economic prosperity and stability of Zimbabwe and the region," the
statement said. "The Secretary-General, through UNDP, will
continue his efforts for a solution."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, the Zimbabwean Government published a list of
804 white-owned farms to be seized without compensation for
landless members of the black majority, reports said.
</P>
<P>
On May 18, Brown told a press conference that he hoped to
encourage international donors to provide funds for Zimbabwe to
compensate white farmers.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "Nobody's going to write a blank check," and
donors needed to be assured that Zimbabwe was committed to a "
transparent, fair and legally enforceable process."
</P>
<P>
The UNDP envisaged the transfer over five years of five
million hectares (12.3 million acres) of land to resettle 150,000
families.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP figures showed that 4,460 large-scale commercial
farms in Zimbabwe currently hold 11.2 million hectares (27.7
million acres) while more than six million people, mostly in
communal areas, occupy 16 .4 million hectares (40.5 million acres).
</P>
<P>
The land ownership dispute erupted in February when black
veterans occupied more than 1,000 white-owned large-scale farms
nationwide, which later led a clash, killing 3 people were killed
and injuring a dozen others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
