<HEADLINE> China Demands Probe into Impact of NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China Friday demanded a
probe into "the possible severe violation" of the humanitarian law
by NATO in its bombing of Yugoslavia, saying that convinced
evidence is needed to support the allegation that there was no
basis for a U.N. investigation into the unilateral NATO air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xu, representative of the Chinese Mission to the United
Nations, told an open Security Council meeting that China fully
supports such an investigation by the International Criminal
Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the tribunal can implement the law in
objective and justice way, not to become a political tool," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the statement in response to the remarks by Carla
del Ponte, the tribunal's prosecutor, at the Security Council, who
said, "Although some mistakes were made by NATO, I am very
satisfied that there was no deliberate targeting of civilians or
unlawful military targets by NATO during the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
However, Belgrade and Western lawyers have produced numerous
complaints and evidence supporting their observation that NATO
forces committed war crimes, including the strike against a bridge
as a passenger train was crossing it, the bombing of a refugee
convoy near Djakovica, and the targeting of the Serbian television
building in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal was set up under a Security Council resolution
seven years ago to prosecute those responsible for atrocities in
the Balkans following the disintegration of Yugoslavia in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the tribunal's stipulations, NATO military
activities in the Balkans are within its jurisdiction, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
