<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Chip Market Sizzles in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide sales of
semiconductors reached an all time record high of 15.2 billion U.S.
dollars in April 2000, up 35.6 percent from a year ago, an
industry group said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Silicon Valley-based Semiconductor Industry Association (
SIA) said the strong growth in chip revenue is being fueled by
cell phone shipments, PC demand, consumer product sales and e-
commerce over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
PC units and consumer electronics sales remained strong during
the first four months of this year, SIA said. Flash memory and
digital signal processing (DSP), used for communications
applications, were especially hot in the market. Flash revenue
jumped 193 percent in the first fourth months of 2000 compared
with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Boston Consulting Group, business to business
e-commerce conducted over the Internet will increase from 92
billion U.S. dollars to nearly 2 trillion dollars by 2003. If this
trend proves correct, SIA said, demand and sales for silicon chips
will be strengthened and increased.
</P>
<P>
In the Asian-Pacific and Japan market, the industry grew at 46
percent and 41.1 percent, respectively from last year. The
Americas market was up 25.7 percent and Europe's sales grew 33.6
percent, according to SIA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
