<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Request $440 million Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique will ask for 440 million
U.S. dollars of loan at next week's meeting in Paris of the World
Bank's Consultative Group, Finance Minister Luisa Diogo said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
She said that the government would bring proposals not only for
urgent rebuilding of infrastructures destroyed by the flood in
February and March, and also for poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The Consultative Group brings together the main donors and
funding agencies, and it is at this forum that the government
presents its funding needs for the year.
</P>
<P>
Diogo said that the new money to be requested at this year's
meeting is in addition to the 453 million dollars pledged for
reconstruction at the donors' conference held in Rome in early
May.
</P>
<P>
The government document for the Paris meeting envisages
external funding of well over 500 million dollars every year for
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government hoped to keep annual debt servicing
down to " no more than 25 million dollars a year", she said.
</P>
<P>
This year the debt servicing is just 23 million dollars instead
of around 70 million dollars as a result of the various debt
cancellations and moratorium declared by creditors in response to
the floods.
</P>
<P>
Diogo said that if all goes well and Mozambique qualifies in
March 2001 for the enhanced Heavily Indebted Poor Countries
Initiative of debt relief, then next year's debt servicing will be
lower than 23 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
