<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 43 Countries Sign New Patent Law Treaty at WIPO Diplomatic Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Forty-three countries signed here
Friday a landmark agreement that will simplify and streamline
procedures for obtaining and maintaining a patent, according to
the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO).
</P>
<P>
The new Patent Law Treaty (PLT) was adopted on June 1, 2000,
and opened for signature on Friday at a ceremony at WIPO
headquarters in Geneva at the end of a three-week diplomatic
conference held under WIPO's auspices.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, a total of 104 countries and three
intergovernmental organizations signed the Final Act of Treaty, a
document that bears witness to the diplomatic conference, its
outcome, and acknowledges the participation of the delegations at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The PLT is open for signature by WIPO member states until June
1,2001. Signature entitles a government to ratify the treaty at
any time. WIPO members that do not sign the PLT within the one-
year period are entitled to accede to the treaty at any time. The
PLT will enter into force after ten countries deposit their
instruments of ratification or accession with the director-general
of WIPO.
</P>
<P>
The countries that signed the PLT on Friday are Algeria,
Austria, Belgium Brazil, Burundi, Croatia, Cuba, Czech Republic,
Democratic People's Republic of Korea, Denmark, Estonia, Gambia,
Ghana, Greece, Haiti Hungary, Israel, Italy, Kenya, Kyrgyztan,
Latvia, Lebanon, Liberia Luxembourg, Madagascar, Malawi, Nigeria,
Poland, Portugal, Republic of Moldova, Romania, SAo Tome and
Principe, Slovenia, Spain, Sudan Switzerland, Togo, Turkey, Uganda,
United Kingdom, United States of America, and Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
