<HEADLINE> Taxi Drivers Sought Over London Bridge Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's anti-terrorist police
hunting bombers who detonated a device on a bridge in west London
were trying to trace two taxi drivers who left their passengers
near the site.
</P>
<P>
Officers said two passengers were dropped off on the south side
of Hammersmith Bridge where the bomb was planted.
</P>
<P>
No-one has claimed responsibility for Thursday's explosion but
there were fears dissident Irish republicans opposed to the
Northern Ireland peace process may be involved.
</P>
<P>
Police were questioning motorists and pedestrians at roadblocks
across west London in an effort to find witnesses.
</P>
<P>
The first cab was seen on the bridge at 02:45 a.m. (01:45 GMT).
It drove from north to south, where it was observed dropping off a
male passenger.
</P>
<P>
It is thought the car then turned around and drove back to the
north side of the Thames.
</P>
<P>
The second taxi was seen on the bridge at 03:40 a.m. (02:40 GMT)
. It drove over from the north side, and stopped briefly on the
south side to drop a passenger and then continued towards Barnes
on the south side.
</P>
<P>
The high-explosive device exploded at 04:30 a.m. (03:40 GMT),
damaging the bridge but not causing any injuries.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, London police sounded the all-clear after a bomb
scare triggered a major security alert in the capital and forced
them to seal off a large area of the City financial district.
</P>
<P>
Police had told people in banks and office buildings in the
Bishopsgate area to stay away from windows and said they might
have to conduct controlled explosions.
</P>
<P>
But by 3.45 p.m. (14:45 GMT) police were lifting road blocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
