<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An international tender will be
called next week for the buyout of a Greek Olympic Airways (OA)
share package following British Airways's failure to table a bid
for up to a 20 percent stake in the Greek national carrier.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this after the collapse of the negotiations between
Greece's Economy and Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou,
Transport and Communications Minister Christos Verelis and the new
British Airways (BA) management in Athens late Friday, Papantoniou
said that the winner of the tender would also take on OA's
management.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, the Greek government signed with BA's
subsidiary Speedwing a contract, which allows the latter to have
the right to manage the ailing Greek national carrier for 30
months in order to shape up its finances and operations.
</P>
<P>
The contract, which expires at the end of next year, gave BA
the option of bidding for up to 20 percent stake in OA.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Verelis will meet with OA's British managing
director Rod Lynch in order to end the cooperation and finalize
the timetable for the withdrawal of Speedwing from OA's management.
</P>
<P>
Verelis said that interests had already been expressed by
foreign banks and Greek investors, but the basic goal was to place
OA in an international partnership in order to survive in the
international competition. 
