<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA President on Special Session on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations General
Assembly Special Session "Women 2000, Gender Equality, Development
and peace for the Twenty-first Century" will review the
implementation of the Beijing Platform for Action and urge further
actions from all governments in this regard, Theo-Ben Gurirab,
President of the General Assembly said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gurirab, who just returned last Wednesday from Beijing, China,
where the Fourth World Conference on Women was held in 1995, said
the special session would focusing on the specific concerns of
women for gender equality, development and peace, and assess how
much has been achieved in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 12 critical areas of concern were spelled out in
the Beijing Platform for Action which called for specific measures
at all levels and much still remains to be done, Gurirab said.
</P>
<P>
The special session, a big gathering, will expect the
participation of Delegates from all 188 Member States and more
than 1,250 nongovernmental organizations, and among them, there
are two prime ministers and four vice presidents, he added.
</P>
<P>
As a follow-up to the Fourth World Conference on Women, the
United Nations General Assembly will convene a special session for
the five-year review of the Beijing Platform for Action, adopted
by the 1995 Conference.
</P>
<P>
This special session will take place in New York, from June 5-
9, 2000, under the theme of "Women 2000: Gender Equality,
Development and Peace for the Twenty-First Century."
</P>
<P>
Also called Beijing+5, the special session will focus on
examples of good practices, positive actions, lessons learned,
obstacles and key challenges remaining. It will consider further
actions and initiatives for achieving gender equality in the new
millennium
</P>
<P>
At the end of the special session, Governments will issue a
political declaration calling for recommitment to the Beijing
Platform for Action.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
