<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Honor Pledges to JMC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Friday called upon African
countries to honor their pledges to the Joint Military Commission
(JMC) to enable full operation and facilitation of the commission
in charge of monitoring ceasefire in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"Logistical and financial problems have paralyzed your (JMC)
work, but we hope that most of these problems will be solved and
appeal for your patience," Presidential Affairs Minister Eric
Silwamba said at the opening of the seventh JMC plenary session in
Zambian capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The minister thanked the countries and organizations for
providing financial and logistic support to the JMC comprising all
warring parties to the DRC conflict, which erupted in August 1998
with the DRC President Laurent Kabila's government backed by
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia on the one side and the rebels
supported by Uganda and Rwanda on the other.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba noted that all the warring parties had complied with
the new ceasefire agreement reached in the Ugandan capital Kampala
in April this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the ceasefire agreement has been holding
was evidence of the seriousness of both sides of the conflict, who
have been accusing each other of violating the ceasefire agreement
signed in Lusaka last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
