<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Rail Travel at Record, But Profits Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) - More people in Britain traveled by
train last year than at any time since 1946. Passengers made 947
million rail journeys, covering 24 billion miles, official figures
show.
</P>
<P>
According to Railtrack, the company that owns the UK's railway,
train punctuality increased slightly, but the percentage of train
services that failed to run more than doubled, from 0.8 percent of
trains to 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The company announced annual profits down by 16 percent, to 360
million pounds, adding that the fall was caused by extra
investment in infrastructure, prompted by demand.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said Railtrack's profits fall was largely a
result of its decision to take a special 61 million pounds charge
for its continuing track maintenance bills.
</P>
<P>
Gerald Corbett, Railtrack's chief executive, said his company
needs an extra 750 million pounds a year from Britain's train
companies if the Government's plans for rail rejuvenation are to
go ahead.
</P>
<P>
However, Railtrack will be forced to cut its investment at the
time of the next general election unless profits recover, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
