<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Shop Prices Fall 1.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) - Shop prices in Britain have fallen in
May for the thirteenth consecutive month to stand at 1.1 percent
lower than a year earlier, which is good news for consumers but
bad for retailers.
</P>
<P>
The British Retail Consortium (BRC) said Friday that food
prices fell slightly faster than non-food goods due to lower
prices of produce, particularly the price of tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
Mark Bradshaw, the BRC acting director general, said: "Whilst
deflation in the high street is great news for customers,
retailers are seeing margins squeezed at the same time as pressure
is applied to their operating costs."
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe the figures can be taken as evidence
that the Bank of England's monetary policy committee does not need
to raise interest rates to combat inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Bank left its main lending rate on hold at 6 percent last
month for the third successive month, which is regarded as an
evidence that UK interest rates are approaching the peak of the
current cycle.
</P>
<P>
In April, the committee raised interest rates by 0.25 percent
to 6 percent, amidst fears that rising house prices and growing
consumer confidence could signal inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
