<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Trade Deficit Widens in First 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's trade deficit widened
to 746 million U.S. dollars in the first four months of this year,
a 82 percent increase over the same period a year earlier, the
Central Bank said Friday.
</P>
<P>
It said in a statement the ever-increasing deficit was due to a
sharp surge in imports which were up 36.1 percent at 2.285 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew by 21.2 percent in the January-April 2000 period
to 1.539 billion dollars from 1.269 billion dollars in the same
period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The bank said agricultural exports increased by 10.7 percent to
302.5 million dollars from 273.2 million dollars in the first four
months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Industrial exports, especially food and beverage and petroleum
products, were up 23.6 percent at 1.186 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rise in imports was reflected mainly in two of the three
main categories -- consumer goods, intermediate goods and
investment goods, which rose by 5.4 percent, 40.8 percent and 46.8
percent, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
