<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's External Debt Reaches 99 Billion Dollars in  1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A report released by the Ministry of Finance Friday said that
the country's debt shot up by four billion dollars in one year to
reach the peak level of 99 billion dollars recorded in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The external debt to the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of the
country stood at 22.3 percent in December 1999 as compared to 24.4
percent in March 1998. The ratio had peaked to 41 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
But in terms of absolute level of debt, India's position
improved from the third largest debtor after Brazil and Mexico in
1991 to ninth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total external debt, 94.34 billion dollars
constituted long-term debt while short-term debt constituted only
4.67 billion dollars, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
