<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet to Link Southern African, World Health Experts Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Health care workers in South
Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho and Swaziland will soon be
hooked up to an internet information network linking them with
HIV/AIDS specialists throughout the world, South African Press
Association reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-based International Association of Physicians in AIDS
Care (IAPAC) will link hospitals and clinics in the five countries
with 10,000 physicians in 52 countries through the internet
medical exchange.
</P>
<P>
Information available on the network will include issues
related to the care of HIV/AIDS sufferers who can not afford
expensive drugs.
</P>
<P>
"We will not be focusing only on the use of anti-retroviral
drugs. We recognize that given the economic situations in the
region access to those drugs is not universal," IAPAC Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Jose Zuniga said in a telephone interview
from Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"We will be looking at such basic things as monitoring,
palliative care and life issues that are relevant to the southern
African experience. That is a goal of this program," Zuniga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
