<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Protect Its Ancient City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Mayor Liu Qi said here
today that construction projects in the capital have to be blend
with the ancient buildings and architecture in the city.
</P>
<P>
He said that any construction project that does not meet with
preservation requirements will not be given the green light. If
construction goes ahead, advanced technologies should be used to
protect historical relics.
</P>
<P>
Li made these remarks at the Urban Development Meeting of
Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of several dynasties, Beijing is one of the
architectural wonders of the world, said Liu, adding that people
should not ignore the preservation of cultural relics as the city
continues to develop rapidly. Preserving ancient relics and sites
in the city is important now and for future generations to come.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the people have to adopt new ways of protecting
the historical city. Preservation is not a burden on the economic
development of the city, but rather provides invaluable economic,
social and cultural resources.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the priority sites for of preservation include
the Forbidden City, the layout of the city and its waterways.
</P>
<P>
He noted that less than one-third of the 222 ancient buildings
earmarked for urgent protection will become museums and memorials.
Those occupying historical buildings will be asked to move out and
find other premises so that restoration work can begin on these
buildings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
