<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Commission Adopts Protocol on Baku-Ceyhan Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 2 (Xinhua -- The Foreign Affairs Commission of the
Turkish parliament adopted on Friday a protocol for a change in the
Baku-Ceyhan Oil Pipeline Agreement between Turkey, Azerbaijan and
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Energy and Natural Resources Cumhur Ersumer and
representatives of Turkey's Pipeline Oil Transportation Inc.
(Botas) briefed the commission on the pipeline during a debate at
the panel session.
</P>
<P>
The parliament's Industry Commission already approved the
protocol to amend part of the pipeline agreement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Following the approval by the parliament's two committees, the
issue will be taken up for discussion in the full parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ersumer said during the Industry Commission debate that all
costs of the part of the pipeline in Turkish territories, estimated
at 1.3 billion U.S. dollars, will be met by the investor
consortium.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that Turkey had extended a fixed-price
guarantee to the investor consortium for the field allocation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on transport of Caspian basin oil to world markets
was signed among the three countries under the promotion of United
States President Bill Clinton, on the sideline of Organization of
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) summit at Istanbul last
November.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said the 1,740-kilometer pipeline, starting from
Azeri Caspian port Baku to Turkish southern port city Ceyhan via
Georgian capital Tbilisi, is of political and strategic importance
rather than a lucrative investment.
</P>
<P>
They considered it a vital move of the U.S.-led western powers
to curb Russian and Iranian expansion of their influence in the
newly-independent Central Asia and Caucasus regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
