<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Undertake Rehabilitation in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
ordered Friday concerned government agencies to immediately
undertake the rehabilitation of areas affected by the conflict in
Mindanao as the Moro rebels took another steps towards peace.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Orlando Mercado of the Department of National Defense
said Friday night that the president approved his recommendation
to set up "zones of peace" in 20 towns and one city in the
affected areas to intensify recovery and rehabilitation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a cabinet meeting in the Presidential Palace,
Mercado told reporters that some 50,691 families or 288,510
persons have been displaced because of the conflict erupted in
April between government troops and Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said the death toll of the conflict includes 160 soldiers
and 66 civilians, while the number of injured includes 650
soldiers and 185 civilians.
</P>
<P>
Mercado and Chief of Staff Angelo Reyes visited Mindanao Friday
morning to praise the soldiers for their heroism and assure Muslim
communities that the government will take care of them.
</P>
<P>
Continuing skirmishes between government soldiers and MILF
guerrillas are still noted in Mindanao despite the signing of a
joint statement by government-MILF peace brokers on Thursday of
their commitment to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Reports said government forces occupied Friday the main
entrance to Camp Abubakar, the MILF' biggest camp in Mindanao.
Government troops have destroyed scores of MILF camps since April.
</P>
<P>
The 15,000-strong MILF has been fighting for more than two
decades to establish an independent Muslim state in Mindanao,
which was flatly rejected by the Philippine government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Silver Up in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ready silver (.999 fineness) ended at 7,840 rupees (182.33 U.S.
dollars) per kilogram, showing a moderate gain of 10 rupees (0.23
dollar) over the previous day's close of 7,830 rupees (182.10
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Raw silver (.916 fineness) rose by 15 rupees (0.35 dollar) to
end at 7,715 rupees (179.42 dollars) per kilogram from Thursday's
level of 7,700 rupees (179.07 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, standard gold and twenty-two-carat gold remained
steady at their previous day's level of 4,365 rupees (101.51
dollars) per 10 grams and 4,040 rupees (93.95 dollars)
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
