<HEADLINE> China-made Trains Handed Over to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of China-made five
passenger trains with diesel electric locomotives were handed
over to the Sri Lankan railway authorities Friday at Fort Railway
Station in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
"The running of the New Diesel Multiple Units from China on Sri
Lankan railways will play an active role in improving and
developing Sri Lanka's railway transportation," said Sri Lankan
Minister of Transport A.H.M. Fowzie when addressing the
inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The trains with diesel electric locomotives, the first of its
kind in Sri Lanka, were produced by Sifang Locomotive &AMP; Stock
Works from Qingdao in eastern China.
</P>
<P>
The five trains are part of the contract to provide 15
passenger trains to Sri Lanka from China.
</P>
<P>
The second batch of five trains has arrived here and the final
batch of five ones is expected to be shipped within this month.
</P>
<P>
The contract worth some 37 million U.S. dollars was signed here
in February last year. Sifang Locomotive &AMP; Stock Works along with
two Chinese companies got the manufacturing contract after
defeating bidders from Korean, Japan and India in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Sri Lanka Zhang Yun, and Sri Lankan
Minister of Fisheries and Aquatic Resources Development Mahinda
Rajapakse were also present at the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
