<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Community Ready to Help End Conflicts in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The international community is ready
to make efforts to help find specific ways to end the Angolan war,
Ibrahim Gambari, U.N. special advisor for African affairs, has
said.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here on Friday said that the U.N. official,
who is currently in Lisbon for an official visit to Portugal, said
the Angolan war can only be resolved by political accord.
</P>
<P>
Gambari, who visited Angola recently, said that he was shocked
by the situation of many hundreds of thousands of war refugees and
displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the war will not end except via political
agreement,"he said, adding that "there is a global perception that
this is the direction we all have to follow."
</P>
<P>
"We clearly saw the terrible destruction of the country and the
setback to development caused by the war," said the envoy.
</P>
<P>
The special advisor to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
stressed that the top priority is to end the terrible war in the
country where successive generations have never known peace.
</P>
<P>
Of the 12.6 million Angolans, 3.7 million are displaced
persons, 1.1 million refugees, Gambari said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is "too much", he stated, urging international
community to help Angola switch from war to peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
