<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Chinese Cities Report Improved Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Most of China's major cities
reported improved quality of air this week owing to widespread
rainfall throughout northern China and slashed production of coal
for heating, the China Environmental Monitoring Center said today.
</P>
<P>
From May 26 to June 2, Lanzhou, a capital city in northwest
China, reported unhealthy air, while Yinchuan, Hohhot,
Shijiazhuang, Shenyang, Urumqi, Chongqing, Xi'an and Changchun,
mostly in northwest and north China, also reported slight air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Twenty cities, including Tianjin, Xining, Beijing, Taiyuan,
Changsha, Wuhan and Guangzhou reported fairly good air. Meanwhile,
Ningbo, Shanghai, Guilin, Xiamen, Zhuhai, Shenzhen, Hangzhou and
10 other cities enjoyed excellent air.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou, Yinchuan, Hohhot and 22 other cities listed suspended
particles as the major pollutants, while sulfur dioxide was the
major pollutant in Changsha, Nantong, Yantai and Guangzhou.
</P>
</TEXT>
