<HEADLINE> Peres Wins Unanimous Backing for Presidential Candidacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Regional Cooperation
Minister Shimon Peres, a Nobel Peace Prize Laureate, was
unanimously confirmed on Friday as candidate for his Labor party to
run for president.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of the 76-year-old former prime minister was
finally approved by the party's central committee, which held an
extraordinary party congress for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
Peres had won the endorsement of the Labor party leadership late
Thursday and the support from the parliamentary caucus of One
Israel ruling coalition, in which Labor party acts as the backbone,
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The presidential election was put into parliamentary schedule
after the incumbent President Ezer Weizman was forced to announce
last Sunday that he will resign by July 11, three years before the
end of his second term.
</P>
<P>
The 76-year-old president was involved in a financial scandal
with a French Jewish businessman and escaped a relevant police
indictment just because the statute of limitations on the charges
had run out.
</P>
<P>
A new president will be elected on July 31 in a secret ballot in
the 120-seat Knesset (Parliament) and be inaugurated a day later,
or on August 1, to serve his seven-year term.
</P>
<P>
Peres, a world-known politician who is one of the major Middle
East peace builders along with late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, enjoys great popularity
both at home and abroad. He won a Nobel Peace Prize in 1994 because
of his contributions to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He seems to have a slight advantage over his major contender
Moshe Katsav, the candidate proposed by the opposition Likud party
on Monday, in several preliminary polls of the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
However, the race will be close when it runs into white-hot
stage and Peres should be wary not to take his victory for granted,
local analysts warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
