<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Vows to Keep 80 Percent Jewish Settlements in Israel Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said Friday that 80 percent of Jewish settlements on the West Bank
will be maintained under Israeli sovereignty under whatever peace
deal to be reached between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the a meeting of the Labor Party's Central Committee
in Tel Aviv that some breakthroughs are within view in the Israeli-
Palestinian negotiations. But no matter what will come out, 80
percent of the Jewish settlements will remain under Israeli
control.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators striving to reach a
framework agreement over final status issues had held two rounds
of "back-channel" talks in the Swedish capital of Stockholm without
achieving substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
Barak interrupted the talks on May 21 by calling back Public
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami over violent demonstrations in the
Palestinian territories pressing for the release of Palestinian
prisoners held in Israeli jail.
</P>
<P>
The talks were resumed on Thursday at a secret location in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Barak paid a flying visit to Lisbon for the
first meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton after the Israeli
withdrawal from South Lebanon. Clinton had intended to help secure
some breakthroughs in the Israeli-Palestinian track before the
Israeli pullback originally scheduled for July. However, an
unexpected collapse of the pro-Israeli South Lebanese Army led to
an early withdrawal of the Israel forces.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Clinton said he would send Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright to the Middle East on Monday to work with
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat "on narrowing the gap
that still remains between them".
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson is
scheduled to arrive in the Middle East on Sunday in an effort to
help overcome the snag in peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Stockholm newspaper Svenska Dagbladet said that Persson's
visit was arranged because of apparent progress in secret talks
between the Palestinian and Israeli representatives in Sweden over
the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
In another bid to boost the Mideast peace process, German
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer will travel to the region on
Saturday to hold separate talks with Barak and Arafat, said the
German foreign ministry on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, leaders of Jewish settlers have revealed that Barak
plans to hand over between 92 percent and 95 percent of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip to the Palestinian Authority under a permanent
settlement.
</P>
<P>
They also learned that there will be three categories of
settlements, including those to be dismantled, those that are to
remain but will be on land under Palestinian sovereignty but linked
to the state of Israel and those that will be annexed to Israel
along with areas that are to stay in Israeli hands.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Palestinian and Israeli negotiators have agreed that
the framework deal, which was due on May 13, will include Israeli
recognition of a Palestinian state and a Palestinian declaration
that the conflict between the two peoples has ended, according to
the Israeli paper Ha'aretz.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis and Palestinians are expected to strike a final
peace treaty before September 13 over the thorniest issues such as
the fate of Jerusalem, the future of the Jewish settlements, border
and water resources.
</P>
<P>
Both sides aim to reach a framework accord first, with mid-June
the latest target date, that would pave the way to the permanent
agreement.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Barak told his party colleagues on
Friday that although peace talks with Syria have not been
resumed, "the door is not closed."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian negotiations resumed at the end of last year
after a nearly four-year break but only were stranded again in
January over such differences as on the return of the Golan
Heights, a strategic plateau captured by Israel in 1967, and
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Since then, there have been incessant international efforts to
bring the two sides back to the negotiating table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Deploy More Security Forces in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
announced Friday at his office that his government will increase
the number of security forces deployed in south Lebanon to 1,000,
local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said in his declaration that Lebanon will deploy security
forces instead of the Lebanese army in south because "we now do not

want to serve as Israeli border guard in the liberated region".
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government quickly set up checkpoints on some main
roads to south after the large-scale Israeli withdrawal on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Hoss expressed hope that the Lebanese army will enter into south
in some appropriate circumstances, and said, "Nothing can impede us
doing
that."
</P>
<P>
The visiting U.N. special envoy Roed Larsen had mentioned the
necessity of putting the Lebanese army in south Lebanon after the
Israeli withdrawal, which is now under the control of the Hezbollah
guerrillas. 
</P>
