<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysians Asked to Preserve Peace, Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Yang di-Pertuan
Agong (King Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah Friday called upon
his countrymen to strive to preserve the country's peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The King expressed his worriness that lately there had emerged
an unhealthy situation among Muslims in this country which could
jeopardize unity among them.
</P>
<P>
The culture of slandering each other would not only give rise
to confusion among Muslims but would also retard their progress
and resilience if left unchecked, the King said in his official
birthday address over Radio and TV Malaysia (RTM) Friday night.
</P>
<P>
He urged Muslims to play their respective roles to strengthen
brotherhood among them, saying conflicts among them would only
create a bad image for them among other races.
</P>
<P>
"As Muslims we should hold firmly to the holy teachings of
Islam which exhorted its followers to always remain united and
collaborative and refrain from making allegations or hurling
slander against each other," the King said.
</P>
<P>
He said "as the entire world Muslim community is facing even
tougher challenges arising from globalization, the borderless
world, the Internet and so on, we should not allow confusion among
Muslims to make things even worse."
</P>
<P>
Urging Islamic scholars to find ways of eliminating confusion
about Islam by providing accurate interpretations, the King said
only with a knowledgeable and united Islamic community which
practice close cooperation could Malaysia, an Islamic country,
become more progressive and respected.
</P>
<P>
Malaysians should be grateful for Malaysia to be always at
peace compared to other developing countries, he said, reminding
the citizens that the vision of a developed and wealthy country
could not be realized if the people practiced negative culture
such as rioting, loafing and breaching the law.
</P>
<P>
The King said the people should support and cooperate with the
government in its efforts to bring about even more rapid
development and progress.
</P>
<P>
He said the era of globalization and growth of information
technology in the new millennium required people to equip
themselves with various skills and IT-linked knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Asking the people to realize the potentials of information
technology and act quickly to become well-informed, more
competitive, efficient and productive, the King said "we should
remain vigilant and strive with even greater determination to
ensure that the country remained safe from external threats."
</P>
<P>
The King lauded the government led by Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad for what he said having succeeding not only in restoring
the country to the pre-financial crisis level but having enhancing
the good name of the country in the eyes of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
