<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Accelerate Dev't Projects in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Friday that it will accelerate development projects in Mindanao in
line with President Joseph Estrada's commitment to develop the
region into the country's food basket and regional economic hub.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Benjamin Diokno of the Department of Budget and
Management said that the plan aims to intensify ongoing pro-poor
programs in areas unaffected by hostilities between government
troops and rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We have a stepped-up plan to accelerate the implementation of
pro-poor programs, especially in areas unaffected by conflict,"
Diokno said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
This would mean mostly the whole of Mindanao since the areas
affected by the conflict comprise only a small portion of the
region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Diokno pointed out that the intensified efforts would cover
agriculture, public works, economic planning, transportation and
communication, education, health, and agrarian reform.
</P>
<P>
He said that from the start of 2000, the national government
has released funds amounting to 2.5 billion pesos (62.5 million
dollars) for the region.
</P>
<P>
Diokno also maintained that the police and military operations
will not affect ongoing development projects in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Government troops and Moro Islamic Liberation Front rebels were
locked in fierce battles recently in Mindanao, resulting in heavy
losses on both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
