<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Urges MILF to Accept Autonomy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government urged the
separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) Friday to accept
meaningful autonomy instead of independence as both sides work to
put a permanent end to the conflict in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said this would bring all
parties a step closer to forging a lasting and genuine peace in
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the MILF would realize that independence is not option.
It is better for them to consider our offer of autonomy," Zamora
said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He also tagged as premature reports that the government may
allow an extension of the peace process after June 30, the
deadline President Joseph Estrada set to wrap up the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"It is not proper to talk of an extension now, the talks are
still ongoing. I believe we can achieve good results," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the government's proposed political package for the
MILF revolves on the expansion of ARMM (Autonomous Region in
Muslim Mindanao), depending on the results of a plebiscite later
this year.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, will allow increased participation for local
government units and regional governments in services devolved by
the national government.
</P>
<P>
Autonomy may also allow MILF fighters to be integrated into the
Armed Forces of the Philippines and Philippine National Police, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Government negotiators maintained Thursday night that the joint
communique they signed with the MILF remains the best deal they
can strike for now.
</P>
<P>
The government and MILF panels signed Thursday night a joint
communique where the MILF expressed openness to meaningful
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Technical working groups of both panels will meet June 7 to
take up the MILF's initial response to the government's proposal.
Both panels are scheduled to meet again on June 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
