<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lead Poisoning Among Shanghai Children Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The rate of children who suffer
lead poisoning in Shanghai has been reduced from 37.8 percent in
1997 to 24.8 percent, according to a research report released in
Shanghai recently.
</P>
<P>
The two-year study, conducted by a group of experts from the
Shanghai No. 2 Medical University, tested 1,972 children aged one
to six.
</P>
<P>
The results indicate that the average content of lead in these
children's blood has been reduced to 76 micrograms from 83
micrograms per liter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Lead in children's bodies can affect their nervous, circulatory,
and digestive systems. The acceptable level of lead is 100
micrograms per liter.
</P>
<P>
Exhaust fumes from automobiles, preserved eggs, pencils, and
paint can all be sources of lead pollution.
</P>
<P>
Local experts attributed the downward trend in lead content in
Shanghai children's blood to the ban on the use of leaded gasoline
in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
They urged that greater efforts be made to do away with other
sources of lead pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
