<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enterprises Encouraged to Invest Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province,
which ranks second in the country in terms of gross domestic
product, plans to set up several production centers in South
America, South Asia and eastern Europe over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Well-performing businesses, especially large and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises, are encouraged to establish subsidiaries
in these centers.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, entrepreneurs from Jiangsu have already
set up more than 350 businesses in other countries, with a total
investment of 155 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
While drawing an increasing amount of overseas capital, China
has been promoting investment abroad since 1998 as part of its
effort to further improve the economy.
</P>
<P>
Many local governments have taken steps to help businesspeople
transfer their production lines to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the country's leading industrial and commercial city,
has opened 545 businesses in some 70 countries. It is now drafting
a new plan to promote investment overseas.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang, another booming province in the east, has just issued
a series of preferential policies for promoting investment in
foreign countries, including easy loans and tax refunds for
exported equipment and raw materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
