<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, France Hold Economic Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sixth Sino-French Economic
Symposium concluded here today.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed housing reform, restructuring the
banking sector, auditing in the enterprise restructuring, as well
as company financing in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Yu Xiaosong, president of China Council for the Promotion of
International Trade, said at the meeting that Chinese enterprises
will participate in the integration of world economy by adopting
international standards in accounting and financing.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting provided an opportunities for French
companies to take part in Chinese enterprise reforms in accounting
and financing.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji Thursday met with former French
President Valery Giscard d'Estaing who is heading a French
delegation to attend the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between China and France grew to an all time
high of 6.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1999, increasing 11 percent
over the previous year. French companies have invested in 1,585
projects in China, worth 5.1 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
