<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tonic Food Banned For Misleading Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Health (MOH)
has punished tonic food manufacturers for falsely misleading the
public by claiming that thirteen kinds of tonic products had
therapeutic function.
</P>
<P>
MOH asked local departments responsible for food hygiene
supervision to suspend production and sales of the products and
fine the manufacturers in accordance with China's Food Hygiene Law,
MOH official Huang Jiansheng said today.
</P>
<P>
The products include calcium supplement, weight-reducing tea,
soya lecithin capsules, and nutritional drinks for men. Some of
these products are widely known throughout China through intensive
promotional advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The calcium supplement, produced by Changjiang Biochemical
Technology Co. Ltd. in east China's Fuzhou City, was described in
TV commercials as "effective in enhancing six centimeters of a
person's height within one month." However, MOH never issued any
license to that purported to make one grow, according to a Health
News Report.
</P>
<P>
Tonic products are enjoying a vast growing market in China as
more Chinese are becoming health-conscious.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is now in charge of examining and approving health-
promotion foods. Ministry officials say that many manufacturers
start to exaggerate their products only after passing strict
examinations and obtaining a permit.
</P>
<P>
MOH issued a circular to local health authorities last November
requesting them not to mislead the public when selling their
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
