<HEADLINE> U.S. Dinosaur Man: World's Most Beautiful Scientist(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Actually, four or five months of field work annually throughout
the world finds him wearing jeans most of the time.
</P>
<P>
When photographers from "People" took his picture, the magazine
's designer said "no" to every piece of clothes he took for the
camera shoot.
</P>
<P>
A jade ring he wears in his left ear is the only fashionable
item adorning the fit scientist.
</P>
<P>
Sereno would have been an artist had he not found his real
interest in vertebrate fossils when he was finishing college.
</P>
<P>
But he always considers it a great advantage to be able to draw
as a paleontologist.
</P>
<P>
He said that he drew all the pictures he showed during his
presentation during his speech himself.
</P>
<P>
While preparing to draw the cover for his reprints, he also
plans to write a book about his worldwide expeditions.
</P>
<P>
"Even my wife was picked up during my expedition," he added.
</P>
<P>
After his global research journey, Sereno found more and more
detailed evidence to support his idea of the origin of birds,
which had been on his mind for at least 15 years.
</P>
<P>
"Some peers thought I went for the publicity without too much
work, but they are wrong," Sereno said.
</P>
<P>
For more than a decade, he has made great contributions to the
study of primitive birds with his unique diagram tree for their
evolution.
</P>
<P>
"As a paleontologist, you never know what will be discovered
tomorrow," he said. "Paleontology is about deep culture. It's not
about a new TV or a better car."
</P>
<P>
"The world without museums would be boring, and there would be
no reason to live," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
