<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Export, Import Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chairwoman of the Central Bureau of Statistic (BPS) Sudarti
Surbakti said at a press conference here Friday that the rise was
backed by the increase of non-oil and gas exports by 3.98 percent
to 3.989 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
She said during January-April 2000, the country's export value
increased by 35.93 percent to 19.100 billion dollars compared to
the same period last year with 14.051 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Surbakti said that Indonesia's import in April
reached 2.312 billion dollars, or 2.91 higher than the 2.247
billion dollars in March.
</P>
<P>
During January-April 2000, an import value of 8.849 billion
dollars was recorded, an increased of 15.24 percent over the same
period last year when 7.679 billion dollars of import was posted,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Import of oil and gas commodities in the first four months
sharply increased by 85.55 percent to 787.3 million dollars, while
non-oil and gas commodities was up by 5.67 percent to 383.3
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, import of raw materials in the period reached 4.993
billion dollars, an increased of 19.69 percent compared to the
same period in 1999, Surbakti said, adding that import of capital
goods also rose by 21.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
"But import of consumption goods during January-March 2000 was
501.1 million dollars, down by 4.79 percent from the same period
last year," Surbakti said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
