<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Okays Tourism Satellite Account Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has approved a
plan to develop the Tourism Satellite Account (TSA), which will
allow economic policy-makers to better understand the economic
contribution of tourism, the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT)
announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
TAT said in a report obtained by Xinhua that the plan will help
precisely identify both the direct and indirect contribution of
the tourism to the country's economy and systematically evaluate
its true economic advantage.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the TSA will help us more efficiently
and effectively develop our future growth strategies," TAT
governor Pradech Phayakvichien was quoted by the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 26-million-baht (670,000 U.S. dollars) budget of the plan
will be spent on conducting extensive studies and surveys to
gather more comprehensive information and statistics about the
country's tourism, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The TSA, which is an intensive information-gathering system of
tourism initiated by the United Nations in 1993, has already been
facilitated by the World Tourism Organisation and is now being
implemented by many countries worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
