<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Insects Come from Eurasia and India: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists recently said
research achievements have shown that the original form of the
insects in southwest China's Tibet came from Eurasia and India.
</P>
<P>
Wang Baohai, researcher with the Sciences Academy of
Agriculture and Stockbreeding of the Tibet Autonomous Region, said
that the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau emerged out of sea in the late
period of the Cenozoic Era, when most of the insects had already
come into being. So it is most likely that the insects in Tibet
came from neighboring Eurasia and India.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the entire development process involved
transformations of sea, islands, peninsula, and land, and the
insects first lived and moved among the islands. So, an insects
community gradually appeared in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, the huge mountains on the north side of
Tibet prevented many insects from coming, while the insects from
India met no obstructions, and many of them entered Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Studies also show that the insects in Tibet love a wet and hot
environment and most of them live in the tropic primeval forests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
