<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Deduces Perching Dinosaur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese paleontologist has
deduced that a small Mesozoic dinosaur could perch on trees and
develop the ability to fly by gliding through the trees.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered to the ongoing Fifth International
Meeting of the Society of Avian Paleontology and Evolution and the
Jehol Biota, Zhou Zhonghe, curator of bird fossils, discussed this
controversial subject of the origin of flight.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, professor with the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology (IVPP),
claimed that Caudipteryx, a theropod dinosaur which lived some 100
million years ago, was able to climb trees.
</P>
<P>
"Fossilized specimens show that this kind of feathered dinosaur
had claws which are necessary for perching animals," said the 35-
year-old bird expert.
</P>
<P>
Academic circles widely believe that Caudipteryx had many
similarities to modern birds.
</P>
<P>
"The lineal ancestors of birds most likely lived in trees,"
Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
The dinosaur's forelimbs gradually became wings which supported
them as they learned to fly, the professor said. At the same time,
the structure of Caudipteryx's feet was almost the same as the
claws of modern birds.
</P>
<P>
While Zhou and several other scientists hold to this new theory,
most researchers who believe in the dinosaur-bird relationship
claim that dinosaurs learned to fly while running fast.
</P>
<P>
"I could list many pieces of evidence for the evolutionary
development from dinosaurs to primitive birds," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Scholars from around the world attending the international
meeting said that Zhou's proposal may arouse another round of
heated discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
