<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3-Month Truce in Indonesia's Aceh Province Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the statement, they said they are ready to take all the
necessary steps to honor the "agreement signed by our
representatives in Switzerland."
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Indonesian government and the separatist
group GAM signed a humanitarian pause accord in Geneva,
Switzerland, on May 12.
</P>
<P>
Friday's statement was signed by Col. (Police Idhwan Karim
representing the government and Nashiruddin bin Ahmed of the GAM
in the provincial capital of Bandar Aceh.
</P>
<P>
The two parties said: "We believe that the conflict between our
armed forces has caused tremendous suffering in Aceh. We are
committed to find ways to successfully stop the violence here. We
will work together in a spirit of cooperation and goodwill to
provide humanitarian assistance to those in need and to improve
the security in Aceh," the statement was quoted by the Antara News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two parties have also agreed to establish a Joint Committee
on Security Modalities and a Joint Committee on Humanitarian
Action.
</P>
<P>
"We will inform the public of the proceedings of the joint
committees and encourage all the people of Aceh to support the
humanitarian pause which comes into effect on June 2, 2000," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the Geneva accord, a joint panel of rebel
leaders, government officials and independent Swiss mediators will
oversee the deal in Aceh. It would regularly report to another "
joint forum" based in Switzerland, which is the highest decision-
making body. The goal would be to extend the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address on Thursday night, President Abdurrahman
Wahid said the humanitarian pause accord would be "the beginning
of a new era of peace" for the people of Aceh after decades of
civil strife.
</P>
<P>
Violence between government security forces and armed GAM
rebels killed more than 400 persons this year. Twenty-three of the
fatalities occurred after the signing of the accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
