<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Hydropower Project Targeted by International Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- At least six international groups
have expressed interest in developing Zambia's 80 megawatt Itezhi
Tezhi hydropower project, the Times of Zambia newspaper reported
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Once completed, the project would boost the country's capacity
to export electricity to Tanzania, Zimbabwe, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo and Kenya, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Peter Mwamfuli, Energy and Water Development
Permanent Secretary, as saying in an interview in Lusaka on
Thursday that the companies expressed interest when bids opened
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Itezhi Tezhi project requires the successful bidder to build a
hydro power plant as there is only one reservoir.
</P>
<P>
"We are moving steadily, we hope we can get the groundwork done
by early next year," Mwamfuli said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government is bracing itself for increased
electricity demand in the region, the official said, citing Kenya
where serious load shedding is taking place due to insufficient
power.
</P>
<P>
On the building of a 67 million U.S. dollar mini-hydropower
station in North-Western Province, Mwamfuli said his ministry is
awaiting a final report before making further recommendations on
the modalities of development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
