<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Vows to Defeat Anti-Referendum Petition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has vowed to defeat a petition filed against the Referendum Act
and Other Provisions Act by Democratic Party (DP) President Paul
Ssemogerere, Ugandan media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Ssemogerere and his likes are trying to attack the referendum
law so that they derail the people, but they will not manage
because we also know the law," the New Vision daily quoted
Museveni as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If he thinks he is making a strong point by going to the
courts of law, we shall show him that he is making no point at
all," Museveni told a consultative meeting attended by Soroti
district Movement and referendum committee members on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The petition, which was dismissed by the Constitutional Court
on technicalities last September, got a new lease of life on
Wednesday after the Supreme Court remitted it to the same court
for hearing.
</P>
<P>
"The referendum was not ordered by the Referendum and Other
Provisions Act, but by the Constitution which is the supreme law
of the land," the Monitor daily quoted Museveni, also chairman of
the ruling National Resistance Movement (NRM), as saying.
</P>
<P>
He accused Ssembogerere and his party of raising "irrelevant"
issues against the NRM including a plot to "block" the June 29
referendum on political systems, said the Monitor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Constitutional Court Thursday set June 6 as the
date to hear Ssemogerere' petition against the Referendum Act and
Other Provisions Act.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the NRM will come out a winner in
the coming referendum late this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
