<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Warns Presidential Aspirants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has warned Environment Minister Ben Mwila, a presidential
aspirant, and other ruling party leaders campaigning for the
presidency that he would take action against them at an
appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
The president told cadres of the ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) Thursday in a northern city of Ndola
that he will make the move to justify his action to discipline MMD
leaders who are not following party regulations by campaigning
prematurely, the Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mwila and all ministers campaigning for the presidency are free
to leave MMD if they fail to comply to party rules and
regulations, Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
"We share a common denominator as a party. Anyone going against
such regulations is free to leave," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mwila announced his candidature for the MMD presidency on May
26, paving the way for him to run for the country's presidency in
the general elections to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
Mwila is one of the country's richest with a business empire
spanning manufacturing, construction, finance and fertilizers. He
helped incumbent President Chiluba defeat former President Kenneth
Kaunda in the 1991 elections and is now seen as a leading
candidate to replace Chiluba in the next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Chiluba has indicated that he would ensure that Mwila
does not become the president and MMD has said it is not the time
now to start the election campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
