<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reforms Methods for Assessment of Research findings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China will reform its methods of
evaluating scientific and technological achievements, and these
new procedures are expected to become effective sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a symposium on the management of scientific and
technological achievements which closed here today, the assessment
of scientific and technological achievements is now conducted by
the government, but will, for the most part, be carried out in
accordance with market considerations in the future.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Science and Technology said
that his ministry started revising the "methods for assessment of
scientific and technological achievements" last September.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua has learned that the ministry put forward the "
management methods for assessment of scientific and technological
achievements" at the just-closed symposium to solicit opinions.
</P>
<P>
The new management methods stipulate that relevant government
departments will be responsible for the examination and appraisal
of scientific and technological achievements that involve state
secrets and those of especially great importance. For the rest,
the great majority of research achievements, qualified social
intermediary organs will be responsible for examination and
evaluation according to certain criteria and regulations.
</P>
<P>
China has issued three methods for the assessment of scientific
and technological achievements since 1961.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smuggling of Imported Wines, Spirits Halted in Shantou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Shantou Customs officers in south
China's Guangdong Province stopped a ship attempting to smuggle 2,
367 cartons of imported wines and spirits worth over 10 million
yuan at sea near the town of Huilai, also in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
In the early hours of May 28, after being alerted to be on the
look-out, a coast guard vessel on patrol in sea waters near
Huilaih spotted a suspicious fishing boat at 2:10 am which refused
to be inspected when requested to do so.
</P>
<P>
The fishing boat was eventually overtaken after 20 minutes of
maneuvers, and was found to have 18 kinds of illegal foreign wines
and spirits on board.
</P>
<P>
The smuggling boat set sail from the Philippines on May 25, but
was quickly found by the coast guard vessel soon after it reached
the Chinese coast near Huilai. The smugglers intended to secretly
unload all the contraband on the nearby coast, but the plan was
aborted.
</P>
<P>
All six people aboard the boat were detained, with all the
contraband commodities confiscated. The case is still under
investigations, said sources from Shantou Customs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
