<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Northwest Development Faces Six Major Problems (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The development of China's vast
northwest area faces six major problems, a group of leading
scientists and scholars said in a report that has been presented
to the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The problems must be properly addressed with if the country's
drive of grand scheme to develop the northwest is to be a success,
they noted.
</P>
<P>
The report from 25 academicians and 20 senior researchers and
engineers of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the Chinese
Academy of Engineering lists the mis-use of water resources in the
arid land as the biggest obstacle.
</P>
<P>
The haphazard use of water resources, such as the backward
irrigation system and poor management, has resulted in the
deterioration of the local environment, including the expansion of
deserts.
</P>
<P>
In the future development plan, water for maintaining the
ecological balance must be guaranteed and a water-conserving
irrigation system should be further promoted.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the management of water resources should be
enhanced through economic and legal methods, the report says. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Northwest Development Faces Six Major Problems (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report lists the area's sub-par educational and scientific
facilities as the second hindrance to the northwest development.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that a special education program be set up to
foster local teachers and to attract skilled outsiders. Education
infrastructure construction and distance education programs should
be given adequate attention.
</P>
<P>
The backward transportation and telecommunications systems are
the third obstacle, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, in the process of tapping the abundant energy and
mineral resources, the northwest should equally consider
environmental protection and the development of renewable
resources such as wind and solar energy.
</P>
<P>
The fifth problem is the irrational industrial structure and
widening gap between cities and rural areas, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that the northwest's industries should shift to
areas in which they have comparative advantages, such as raw-
material processing and textile industries. In addition,
urbanization drive and the construction of medium-sized and small
cities should be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Finally, more efforts should be made to develop water-saving
and ecological agriculture in the northwest area, the report noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> To Be or Not to Be: China's Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- China's automotive industry must
adopt effective means to tackle the unprecedented challenges it
will face after the country enters the World Trade Organization (
WTO), says the latest issue of Outlook, the country's most
authoritative news weekly.
</P>
<P>
"After China joins the WTO, the automotive industry will face
great challenges from the outside, so the industry is at a crucial
historic moment," the magazine's June 5 issue says in a signed
article.
</P>
<P>
As globalization is an irreversible trend in the development of
the auto industry, China's automotive industry will unavoidably be
driven into this trend, whether China joins the WTO or not, the
article argues.
</P>
<P>
Faced with globalization, China's automobile sector has
weaknesses such as small scale, irrational allocation, and low
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the global auto industry is shifting to
developing countries in the process of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"That means globalization not only brings about challenges, but
also provides opportunities for China. The crux of the problem is
how to create the best investment environment to attract foreign
investment," the article says.
</P>
<P>
Since combining domestic motor enterprises to form several huge
enterprise groups and building small joint ventures have both
proved ineffective, the article puts forwards a better alternative,
that is, Sino-foreign cooperation on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
The ideal partner for China's automotive industry would be
large multinational enterprises that are not only willing to set
up research centers in China, but also intend to build large-scale
production bases, the article says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
