<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) is
trying to establish an unofficial buffer zone between Israel and
Lebanon at sea, in an effort to prevent maritime mishaps that could
cause friction and derail efforts to restore peace in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel confirmed Thursday that the force
commander, Major General Seth Kofi Obeng, is trying to arrange an "
informal separation zone with the consent of both sides."
</P>
<P>
This follows a number of incidents in which Lebanese fishermen
have encroached on Israel's territorial waters, claiming that they
were operating in Lebanese waters.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had reshuffled the workload
of his two negotiating teams on the framework and permanent status
agreements with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
A coordination meeting was held this week between the head of
the formal team, Oded Eran, and attorney Gilad Sher, Barak's envoy
to the "secret" track being run by Public Security Minister Shlomo
Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
A senior Barak associate says that the Ben Ami-Sher team will
discuss fundamental issues with senior Palestinian officials Abu
Ala and Hassan Asfour. Eran will deal with secondary issues, such
as routine security arrangements between Israel and the
Palestinians, the legal appendix to the agreement, and the economic
aspects.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton, hoping to clinch one final
Middle East peace coup before he leaves office, said Thursday he
would like to convene an end-of-month summit with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Barak flew nine hours to Lisbon and back to spend just an hour
and a half with Clinton. The two discussed ideas to bridge the
remaining gaps between Israel and the Palestinians and pave the way
for a final status agreement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross will visit the region this
weekend and be followed next week by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. They will meet with leaders and negotiating teams and
report back to Clinton on the state of progress.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Thursday night that
Jerusalem will remain united under Israeli sovereignty and will
never be divided.
</P>
<P>
Barak, speaking at a ceremony at Ammunition Hill marking
Jerusalem Day, said that the Holy City should not be compared to
other territories captured during the Six-Day War. The Day
commemorates the anniversary of the city's "unification" in the
1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem shall forever remain ours because it is in our souls.
Never again will Jerusalem be under foreign sovereignty. Only he
who is cut off from Israel's heritage could allow the thought of
dividing the city to pass his lips," said Barak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
