<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Hostages to Be Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's hostage crisis seems to be
close to its end as an agreement was reached Thursday night
between the military authorities and Hostage-taker George Speight.
</P>
<P>
According to Australian Associated Press, Speight told
reporters at the parliament house complex Friday that "All going
well, my plan is to release them (the hostages) before the Great
Council of Chiefs meeting on Monday."
</P>
<P>
Final details of the deal to set free Prime Minister Mahendra
Chaudhry and his MPs were being hammered out Friday, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Speight and military rulers made a major breakthrough Thursday
night when they agreed Fiji's powerful Great Council of Chiefs
would decide finally whether to accept Speight's demands for an
interim civilian government, or continued military rule.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs will have a meeting next Monday but they are
reported having had already agreed to Speight's demand to play an
influential role in the country's political arena.
</P>
<P>
Speight insisted he has "leadership potential" and began
lobbying chiefs to back his plan for power.
</P>
<P>
Fiji's former Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and his cabinet
members were taken hostage on May 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
