<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Build Two Diesel Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Power and Lighting
Company has concluded two agreements which will accelerate the
delivery of two 55- megawatt diesel power generating plants on a
fast-track basis.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed Thursday with a consortium
consisting of Deutz (UK) Limited and Burmeister and Wain
Scandinavian Contractor, Friday' s East African Standard newspaper
quoted the company's Managing Director Samuel Gichuru as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two power plants, to be located in Lanet and Eldoret, both
in Rift Valley Province, will cost 135 million U.S. dollars,
Gichuru said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Lanet plant is expected to be operational in next
June while the Eldoret plant will start producing electricity in
next July.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreements is part of the measures
undertaken by the Kenyan government to minimize the adverse effect
of the ongoing 12-hour power rationing program on customers.
</P>
<P>
Kenya began power rationing last September due to a two-year
drought leading to the lowest water level of major energy
reservoirs, leaving an electricity shortfall of between 154 and
360 megawatts in the off-peak and peak hours respectively.
</P>
<P>
The government last week introduced a 12-hour power rationing
schedule starting this week, with industrial and commercial
consumers having power between 6:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. everyday
except Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
