<HEADLINE> 12 Tanzanian Fishermen Still Held Hostage by Burundian Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Twelve Tanzanian fishermen
are still being held hostage by the Burundian army who suspect
them to be members of a rebel group in the central African
country, the Guardian newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania People's Defense Forces (TPDF) is negotiating with
the Burundian army for the release of the fishermen, said
Tanzanian Chief of Defense Forces (CDF) Robert Mboma on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said TPDF has already sent the Burundian army the names of
the captives to prove that they are Tanzanians who just crossed
the border into Burundi in search of fish.
</P>
<P>
According to the military chief, the fishermen, mistaken as
gunmen loyal to the rebel National Council for Defense of
Democracy (CNDD) in Burundi, were arrested last Sunday in a war
zone after crossing the border into Burundi on Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 fishermen were arrested after they crossed to the
 Burundian side of the border which has been forbidden for fishing
 activities, but 14 of them managed to escape from captivity soon
after being taken in a boat to Kabonga in Burundi where they were
kept hostage by the Burundian soldiers. 
</P>
