<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Worry About Recession, Stock, Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A public opinion poll released
Thursday shows most Americans expect a recession, a dramatic drop
in the stock market and significantly higher interest rates in
next four years.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility that a recession will hit U.S. economy, the
answers were: very likely, 14 percent; somewhat likely, 42 percent;
not likely, 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the stock prices will drop dramatically, the answers
were: very likely, 15 percent; somewhat likely, 35 percent; not
likely, 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question that if they think that interest rates
will rise dramatically, 28 percent voters said it is very likely,
44 percent thought it somewhat likely, while only 24 percent said
it is not likely.
</P>
<P>
The poll of 1,002 likely voters, taken in May 29-31 by pollster
John Zogby, found 40 percent of respondents expected a
substantial increase in unemployment in the next four years, while
55 percent didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found a virtual dead heat in the presidential
race between Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic candidate, and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, his Republican rival.
</P>
<P>
Asked if a recession was more likely under Bush or under Gore,
30 percent said Bush, 23 percent said Gore and 35 percent thought
either or neither.
</P>
<P>
But asked if they personally would be better off under Bush or
Gore, 43 percent said Bush and 39 percent said Gore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
