TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori on Friday
dissolved the House of Representatives for a general election set
on June 25 prior to a no-confidence motion against his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The lower house was dissolved at the outset of a plenary
session from 1 p.m. (local time) Friday after Speaker Soichiro Ito
read out a dissolution rescript from Japanese Emperor Akihito,
which was signed by Mori, for the chamber's first election in
three years and eight months. A no-confidence motion against
Mori's cabinet was presented to the plenary session, but the lower
house was dissolved before deliberations on the motion could begin.
(Japan-Lower House-Dismissal)
</P>
