<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hostage Taker Shot Twice in Head, Critically Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A gunman, who held more than three
dozens of children hostage for 28 hours, was shot in the head
twice by a police sniper and was critically injured, police
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Police disguised as television camera crew lured the Tunisian-
born man, 39, into a fake interview and then shot him in the head.
The gunman, with a history of mental problems, now remains in a
Luxembourg hospital.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five children and three adult teachers were rescued
unhurt. They were all safe and sound after the ordeal that started
on Wednesday afternoon at Wasserbillig near the Luxembourg-Germany
border.
</P>
<P>
The incident was not the first in recent years in European
countries.
</P>
<P>
In May 1993, 21 children aged between three and four were taken
hostage in a nursery school near Paris. The gunman released 15
children and police rescued the rest kids.
</P>
<P>
In February 1994, a man armed with a hand grenade held two
children, a teacher and a school bus driver hostage in Ukraine.
All the hostages were rescued unhurt.
</P>
<P>
In December 1995, gunmen detonated two hand grenades to kill
three children and injured nine others in Russia. A fourth child
died four days later from the injury sustained from the grenade
blasts.
</P>
<P>
On March 13, 1996, at Dunblane of Scotland, 16 children aged
between four and six together with their teacher were shot dead in
a nursery school gym. The gunman took his own life after the
shooting spree.
</P>
<P>
A gunman shot and seriously injured nine people in a British
school in July 1996 before he was overwhelmed by the police. Among
the injured were three children aged between three and four.
</P>
<P>
On May 15 this year, a man took 25 children and several of a
day-care center's staff hostage in Norway. The gunman released 20
children and eight of the 10 nursery school staff. The incident
ended with no harm to the hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
