<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For Third Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose for the third
consecutive day in Tokyo Friday, led mainly by high-priced
information and technology issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained 105.76 points, or 0.63
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 16,800.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 14.47 points or 0.94 percent to 1,556.
45.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index climbed as high as 16,941.42 in the morning
session, but lost momentum in the afternoon, with traders taking
profits ahead of Friday's announcement of U.S. employment data for
May, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 783.50 million
shares from Thursday's 654.43 million.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced issues led overall share prices higher, while
issues which have drawn active buying recently succumbed to profit-
taking, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The gain in leading issues came after New York's Nasdaq
composite index surged 181.59 points to 3,582.50 on Thursday, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Gainers included brokerage houses, wholesalers and nonferrous-
metal makers, while paper, rubber and real estate issues were
among losers.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 732 to 541 despite the gains in the Nikkei and TOPIX, with
119 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
