<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Descendants of Great Wall Guards Repair Fortress (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Descendants of ancient warriors who
guarded the 6,700-kilometer Great Wall have spent the past nine
months repairing a section of the structure in north China,
carrying stones on their backs up the side of a mountain to fix
the deteriorating fortress.
</P>
<P>
"I can't think of anything that could make me more excited than
rebuilding the Great Wall," said Su Wenyu, the 40-year-old head of
Xinguan village, Pingding County in north China's Shanxi Province,
who spearheaded the project and is a long-distant relative of a
former Wall soldier.
</P>
<P>
"People can hardly believe that this part of the Great Wall was
almost left to ruin in the desolate mountains just a few years ago,
" said Su, who with his 700 fellow villagers has been working on
the section known as Guguan Pass.
</P>
<P>
This segment of the Wall, 400 kilometers west of Beijing, was
built during the Warring States Period (475-221 B.C.) and is one
of the Wall's four renowned passes. The three others are
Juyongguan Pass, Daomaguan Pass, and Jiayuguan Pass, where the
Wall ends in the west.
</P>
<P>
Guguan Pass has been repaired several times throughout history,
and was designated a cultural relic under key protection by the
Shanxi Provincial Government in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Men and women, old and young, have toiled for nine months to
return to its former glory a 620-meter portion that once was
safeguarded by their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
"The work was a tough job compared to planting several thousand
mu of crops on flatland because we have had to carry bricks and
stones on our shoulders up to the mountains," Su said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Descendants of Great Wall Guards Repair Fortress (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Su was told that the stone, and mortar should look similar to
the original materials used to build for Wall. Su's team of
workers used a mortar mixture of lime, cement, ash and sand.
</P>
<P>
Citing the beacon towers restored as an example, Su explained
that the bricks used to build the beacon towers were the same as
those used in restoring the ancient town of Pingyao in Shanxi
Province, which has been inscribed into the World Heritage List by
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Su hopes that the new and improved Guguan Pass will serve a
special purpose.
</P>
<P>
"Our ancestors built the Great Wall to keep out marauding
nomads so that they could live a peaceful life," he said. "We,
their offspring, have rebuilt the Great Wall to attract tourists
so that we can live a better life."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
