<HEADLINE> Pakistan Court Asked to Award Death to Ex-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's High Court of Sindh (
SHC) has admitted an appeal seeking enhancement of life term upto
death sentence for former Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif who had been
convicted in a plane hijacking case.
</P>
<P>
A full bench of SHC comprising Chief Justice Saiyed Saeed
Ashhad, announcing the order Friday morning, said the appeal
raised will be heard from June 12 on day-to-day base, sources from
Sindh capital of Karachi told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The appeal were filed by Advocate General of Sindh representing
the state of Pakistan, challenging April 6 judgment by Anti-
Terrorism Court (ATC) in Karachi which awarded Sharif life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution also filed another appeal which challenged the
acquittal of Sharif's six co-accused including his brother Shahbaz
Sharif in the hijacking case.
</P>
<P>
The case pertains to alleged hijacking of a civilian plane from
Colombo, Sri Lanka, to Karachi on October 12, 1999, which the then
Chief of Army Staff and now Chief Executive of Pakistan, General
Pervez Musharraf, was on board.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Terrorism Court, in its judgment, convicted Sharif and
awarded two life terms for the hijacking and concomitant terrorism
but acquitted the other six accused.
</P>
<P>
However, Sharif's counsel had filed an appeal to SHC earlier
against the conviction of the ousted prime minister and sentence
to him including jail term and fine of 200 million rupees (3.78
million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
