<HEADLINE> Japan Welcomes DPRK Leader Kim's Visit to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Japanese leaders on Friday welcomed
the visit to China by Kim Jong Il, leader of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), expressing the hope that the
visit will give a positive impetus to the forthcoming first-ever
inter-Korean summit and Japan-DPRK talks on establishing
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
"It's very good that (the DPRK) is taking action in the
international community," Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki and
Foreign Minister Yohei Kono, at a separate press conference,
stressed the visit is also expected to bring positive results to
the Japan-DPRK talks on the normalization of diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Kono said the visit "underlined consistency in the DPRK's
recent active diplomatic activities... and is expected to give a
positive impetus to the inter-Korean summit" slated for June 12-
14 in Pyongyang between Kim and South Korean President Kim Dae
Jung.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the inter-Korean summit will move
the Korean Peninsula in the direction of easing tensions by
positively affecting the Japan-DPRK negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Kim, general secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers
Party of Korea, visited China from Monday to Wednesday and held
talks with Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
</TEXT>
