<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Helps Contain Southern US Wildfire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Firefighters in northern New
Mexico got unexpected help as rain fell in the Sangre de Cristo
mountains, where a fire has charred more than 25,000 acres of land,
local authorities reported late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"At first we thought we were going to get dry lightning, but
it's real rain," Maria Garcia, a fire information officer, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Just weeks after Los Alamos being devastated by the worst
wildfire in New Mexico's history, another fire broke out Monday,
sweeping 6,500 acres Tuesday and more than 25,000 acres till
Thursday. The blaze, being held along the Gallinas Canyon ridge,
is still threatening water supply for the town of Las Vegas, New
Mexico, which has 18,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
About 900 firefighters, including 23 so-called hotshot crews of
full-time wildfire specialists, were fighting the wildfire. Eight
air tankers and six helicopters continued to drop water and fire
retardant over the ponderosa and mixed-conifer forest, while
bulldozers cut 50-foot firebreaks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Interagency Fire Center's Web site
indicated on Thursday that fires were also burning in Florida,
Arizona, California, Colorado and Utah. And fire officials warned
that most of the southern United States was at high risk for fires
because of hot, dry weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
More than 11 southern states remain at high risk for wildfire,
according to U.S. Forest Service officials, who said nearly 600,
000 acres of land had been consumed by wildfires in the region
since January, well above average.
</P>
<P>
"The areas suffering from the drought seem to be experiencing
the worst of it now," said Denny Truesdale, assistant director for
fire management at the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
Truesdale warned that northern states were also at risk for
wildfires as the summer months arrive.
</P>
<P>
"You could certainly get fires moving north throughout the
United States up towards the Rocky Mountains and the Pacific
Northwest as the season progresses," he said in an interview
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
