<HEADLINE> Bhutan Buys More Time on Refugee Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bhutanese government sent a
response Thursday to the Nepali Foreign Ministry stating that it
needed more time to discuss the differences relating to refugee
issues between the two countries, a foreign ministry source said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The Bhutanese government sent us a letter, which says it is
still discussing on the points raised by Nepal and will need some
more time," said Lilap Sharma, a Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
The 9th ministerial talks between Nepal and Bhutan held in
Thimpu, Bhutan on May 22-25 was inconclusive, as the Bhutanese
side asked for one-week's time to ponder over Nepal's proposals.
</P>
<P>
"The differences still persist on the modality of verification,
namely the Nepalese side insists on verification on family basis,
while the Bhutanese side wants it to be conducted one by one,"
said Sharma.
</P>
<P>
Despite the differences, the Nepali Foreign Ministry is hopeful
that the verification will begin within two months, as agreed at
the 9th ministerial talks, said Sharma.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here believe that verification is not likely
to begin within two months due to Bhutan's indecision.
</P>
<P>
The verification will divide the 100,000 Bhutanese refugees
living in eastern Nepal into four categories: Bhutanese who were
evicted, Bhutanese who emigrated, Bhutanese with criminal record
and non-Bhutanese.
</P>
<P>
The categories will be the basis for repatriation of the
refugees who were evicted from Bhutan in 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
