<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Lower House Dissolved For General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori
on Friday dissolved the House of Representatives for a general
election set on June 25 prior to a no-confidence motion against
his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The lower house was dissolved at the outset of a plenary
session from 1 p.m. (local time) Friday after Speaker Soichiro Ito
read out a dissolution rescript from Japanese Emperor Akihito,
which was signed by Mori, for the chamber's first election in
three years and eight months.
</P>
<P>
A no-confidence motion against Mori's cabinet was presented to
the plenary session, but the lower house was dissolved before
deliberations on the motion could begin.
</P>
<P>
Japan's four opposition parties, the Democratic Party of Japan
(DPJ), the Japanese Communist Party (JCP), the Liberal Party (LP)
and the Social Democratic Party (SDP), submitted the motion to the
lower house Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties accused Mori of violating the country's
constitution by his recent controversial remark that Japan is a
divine nation with the emperor at its center.
</P>
<P>
Mori's cabinet is expected to hold an extraordinary meeting to
formally fix the June 25 election date. A 12-day official campaign
period begins on June 13.
</P>
<P>
In the election, more than 1,200 candidates will vie for 480
seats in the lower chamber, following a February legislation to
reduce the number of proportional-representation seats by 20 from
this election.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, consisting of the Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP), the New Komeito party and the New Conservative Party,
aims to win a comfortable majority and keep its grip on power.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, which currently holds a combined 336
seats in the 500-seat lower house, needs 254 seats to hold at
least the same number as the opposition in all lower house
standing committees, while still chairing all of them.
</P>
<P>
The opposition bloc, meanwhile, plans to target its attack on
Mori's "divine nation" remark that sparked an uproar and dragged
down Mori's approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to question the process of the transfer of power
to Mori after late Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was rushed to
hospital on April 2 due to a stroke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
