<HEADLINE> Indonesia Still Considers Developing Nuclear Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Atomic Energy
Agency (Batan) is still keen to establish nuclear power plants in
the country, despite fears that earthquakes and volcanic eruptions
could lead to meltdown and radiation fallout, a national newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
It said that apart from nuclear energy, Batan is also
concentrating on the production of genetically modified foods, as
well as genetics technology to breed bigger and fatter livestock.
</P>
<P>
"Our main inventions in the field of genetics and plant
engineering have created excellent rice and corn seeds, as well as
soybeans, green beans, and phenomenal cattle breeding. All of this
is to be socialized among the public without any remuneration,"
Head of Batan, Iyos R Subki was quoted by the Indonesian Observer
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Batan, which is funded by the Research and Technology Ministry,
has a test nuclear reactor at Serpong, the country's West Java
province, which is powered by Uranium 238 (U-238).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Head of Research and Development of Batan, Wuryanto
said that Batan is also considering the feasibility of
constructing nuclear power plant in Indonesia and is paying strict
attention to safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia's power plants could possibly be erected on
ships, which would make them mobile and able to provide energy to
various regions.  
</P>
