<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks Moody's for Rating Upgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand (BOT) has told
Moody's Investor Service, a famous credit rating agency that Thai
financial institutions have recovered from the financial crisis
and they deserve a ratings upgrade, a report from the bank said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
BOT officials had reiterated to Moody's that Thai financial
institutions had secured sufficient funds as required by
regulators to cover loan-loss provisions and that they are capable
of expanding their business without the necessity to raise capital
until 2001, it said.
</P>
<P>
The officials, it said, also pointed out to the rating agency
that some Thai commercial banks had shown signs of improvement,
witnessed by first quarter reports of net earnings.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, without required provisions several more banks would
have posted net profits in the first quarter and that is a
positive signal," it added.
</P>
<P>
Lack of new lending, however, is now the only factor that
impedes the banks' growth, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Moody's rates Thailand with the grade of "Ba1",
which means low investment grade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
