<HEADLINE> U.S. NMD could spark New Global Arms Race, Germany warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
told U.S. president Bill Clinton, who is currently on a week-long
European tour, that the U.S. National Missile Defense (NMD) system
could spark a new round of global arms race.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour talk with Clinton, Shroeder told reporters
that he is worried over U.S. development of the NMD system and his
country will do whatever it can to deter any possible global arms
race sparked by the NMD.
</P>
<P>
He said he also exchanged views on the current Russian
situation with Clinton before his upcoming visit to Russia, part
of his European trip. Both sides indicated they have common
interests in supporting Russia as a politically and economically
stable partner of the west.
</P>
<P>
Clinton emphasized good relations the United States enjoyed
with Germany in the past 50 years and said Germany will become
more important to United States in the 50 years to come.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Berlin Thursday afternoon for a three-day
visit to Germany, he met with German President Johannes Rau and
Angela Merkel, Chairman of Germany's opposition Christian
Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
Before his visit to Germany, Clinton attended the U.S.-EU
summit in Portugal, which currently holds the rotating EU
presidency, and held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
on the latest developments in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Barak planned to talk with Schroeder and Clinton while
attending an international conference called "The 21 Century
Modern Governance" in Berlin Friday but the trip was canceled.
Germany hosts the two-day conference at which leaders from 14
countries under center-left or left party rule will be present.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will fly to Russian Saturday and conclude his current
European trip in Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
