<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Etna Volcano Erupts Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Mount Etna, located on Italy's
Mediterranean island of Sicily, erupted briefly again Thursday
after its latest eruption on April 16, shooting up a black column
of ash, gas and steam about two kilometers into the air.
</P>
<P>
Smoke started to burst out of one of Mount Etna's southern
craters at about 9:00 a.m. local time and the black column could
be seen within a radius of dozens of kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The eruption, which ended half an hour later, send a large
amount of ash to the city of Catania at the foot of the mount,
affecting transportation in the city and sending residents
frequently sweeping streets and their gardens.
</P>
<P>
Lava streams flew along slopes of the volcano, but none of the
nearby villages were believed to be in danger.
</P>
<P>
The crater, which burst Thursday, was formed in 1971 and is the
youngest on Mount Etna. The 3.5-kilometer-high Etna, the largest
and most active volcano in Europe, has erupted frequently since
the beginning of this year and Thursday's eruption was the 59th, a
record high in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Seismologists, who monitor the volcano around-the-clock at an
observation post, said that such activities will not endanger
nearby towns.
</P>
<P>
During a 1992 eruption, lava streams temporarily endangered the
7,000 residents of Zefferana on Etna's lower slopes. But the grand
view of the volcano's eruption and picturesque woodland and
orchard on the mountain's slopes make the area a magnet for
tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Geologist Donates Dinosaur Fossils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese geologist has donated
to the state 60 fossilized dinosaur eggs and more than 200 pieces
of dinosaur fossils found by himself on his won.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six-year-old Zhang Pulin, a retired senior engineer from
Jilin Provincial Geological Investigation Institute, also donated
his writings about the excavation sites and his research on the
findings.
</P>
<P>
Zhang discovered the fossils in central Jilin province,
northeast China, last summer.
</P>
<P>
The dinosaur fossils include tooth, backbones, bones and
muscles, and claws, according to experts from the Chinese Academy
of Sciences. They said that these fossils belong to a group of
meat-eating and grass-eating dinosaurs. Zhang's discoveries also
include some rare dinosaur eggs.
</P>
<P>
Before his retirement, Zhang had made a large number of
geological discoveries, including the "Manchurian fish group,"
later named after him as "Pulin fish of Baojiatun."
</P>
<P>
Zhang's donations are now kept in the Jilin Provincial
Geological Museum, said to be the second largest of its kind in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The museum, built in 1954, boasts more than 30,000 collections,
including three sets of complete dinosaur skeletons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
