<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Cuts Growth Target for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A worsening peace and order
situation in Mindanao is taking its toll on the Philippine economy,
forcing the government to lower its overall economic growth target
for 2000,Business World said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Philippine Finance Secretary Jose Pardo as
saying that the government is now aiming at only a four percent
growth rate for the gross domestic product (GDP), instead of the
original five percent target.
</P>
<P>
"We are standing pat at 4 percent, and 5 percent will be
elusive.Whereas before, it was within reach we had to temper it,"
said Pardo,stressing that "the lower end is what we are looking at
due to the Mindanao problem."
</P>
<P>
According to Pardo, the lowered economic target was discussed
on Wednesday by the Economic Coordination Council in the
Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The government was originally targeting the GDP to grow by four
percent to five percent. The gross national product (GNP), or GDP
plus the income from foreign sources, is forecast to grow by 4.5
percent to 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
While the government has yet to determine the economic impact
of the conflict in Mindanao, Pardo admitted it would put a dent of
the state's expenditure program.
</P>
<P>
But the Finance chief said it is still committed to a 62.5-
billion-peso (1.56 billion U.S. dollars) budget gap despite the
higher expenditures in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Pardo said the government has come up with belt-tightening
measures to cushion the impact of the Mindanao conflict on the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Since April this year, the heavy fighting between government
troops and Moro Islamic Liberation Front rebels has cost hundreds
of lives on the two sides. The battle also forced more than 200,
000 people to flee their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
