<HEADLINE> Indonesian Unrest Blamed on Soeharto Supporters: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Minister Juwono
Sudarsono said he believed supporters of former president Soeharto
were behind the series of riots and disturbances plaguing the
country recently.
</P>
<P>
He said supporters of Soeharto were stirring up violence to try
to shake the government of President Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
"These incidents were to anger and confuse Gus Dur (as the
president is known), but Gus Dur will remain strong and has said
he will fight all such attempts," Sudarsono was quoted by national
newspapers Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he thought followers of Soeharto were behind the
attacks, Sudarsono said: "Yes, and based on the information which
I have received from military intelligence sources, these people
are in Jakarta."
</P>
<P>
At least 47 people were injured on Sunday when a bomb exploded
in a church in Medan, some 1,425 kilometers northwest of Jakarta.
Bombs were also found at two other churches.
</P>
<P>
Violence in North Maluku has flared up again with dozens killed
in attacks on mostly Christian villages on the remote island of
Halmahera, about 2,800 kilometers northeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, a grenade exploded in Ambon, capital of Maluku,
killing two people. The incident has caused tensions to rise again
in the battle-torn province, which has been hit by religious
conflicts for over 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Tension in North Maluku and Maluku has been fanned by the
arrival of more than 2,000 hard-line Muslim volunteers from a
group which has vowed a jihad (holy war) in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sudarsono said he had information that followers of Soeharto
were helping fund the jihad fighters.
</P>
<P>
The 78-year-old Soeharto is under house arrest and Attorney
General Marzuki Darusman said he expects to bring a corruption
case against the former ruler by August.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was pushed from power in May 1998 amid mass social
unrest and economic chaos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
