<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Meets Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
met here Thursday with visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton for
talks on a wide range of bilateral and international issues.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders focused on Russian issues during their two-hour
talks, both underlining the importance of maintaining partnership
with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The German Chancellor said that he and his American guest both
wished Russia stable political and economic situation, stressing
that the world, especially Europe, needs to develop intact
relationship with Russia.
</P>
<P>
They exchanged views on the national missile defense program
that the United States has been engaged in.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder expressed concern about the program, warning it would
spark a new round of arms race.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders expressed satisfaction at the development of
bilateral relations during the past half century, saying the
German-U.S. ties in the coming 50 years will become more important.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed more practical issues ranging from
international child custody disputes to security concerns for a
long-delayed new U.S. Embassy in Berlin, the restored German
capital.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a fund to compensate former Nazi slave and
forced laborers was also included in their talks.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting Schroeder, Clinton, who arrived here Thursday
from Lisbon for a three-day visit, met with his German counterpart,
Johannes Rau, and newly-elected Chairman of the Christian
Democratic Union Angela Merkel.
</P>
<P>
He will fly Friday to Aachen, a western city in Germany, to
receive the International Charlemagne Prize, awarded for 50 years
by Aachen city leaders to world leaders who have promoted European
unity.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the U.S. president will attend in Berlin a 15-
nation summit meeting of center-left governments that is to focus
on "Progressive Governance for the 21st century," then leaves
Germany on the same day for Moscow for his first meeting with
Russian President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
During his last European tour before his term expires, Clinton
will also visit Ukraine after Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
