<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Decides to Dissolve Lower House For Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori
and his cabinet decided Friday morning to dissolve the House of
Representatives in the afternoon for a general election on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The dissolution is expected to take place during a plenary
session this afternoon, Japanese government officials said.
</P>
<P>
A no-confidence motion against Mori's cabinet will be presented
to the plenary session, but the dissolution rescript is expected
to be handed to lower house Speaker Soichiro Ito before the motion
is discussed, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's four opposition parties, the Democratic Party of Japan,
the Japanese Communist Party, the Liberal Party and the Social
Democratic Party, submitted the motion to the lower house
Wednesday after the opposition-proposed censure motion against
Mori's cabinet was voted down by the ruling coalition at the House
of Councilors.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties accused Mori of violating the
constitution by saying that Japan is a divine nation where the
emperor was at the center.
</P>
<P>
Once the lower chamber is dissolved, the Japanese cabinet will
meet again to fix the June 25 election date to follow a 12-day
official campaign period beginning on June 13.
</P>
<P>
In the election, more than 1,200 candidates will vie for 480
seats in the lower chamber, following a February legislation to
reduce the number of proportional-representation seats by 20 from
this election.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, consisting of the Liberal Democratic
Party, the New Komeito party and the New Conservative Party, aims
to win a comfortable majority and keep its grip on power.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, which currently holds a combined 336
seats in the 500-seat lower house, needs 254 seats to hold at
least the same number as the opposition in all lower house
standing committees, while still chairing all of them.
</P>
<P>
The opposition bloc, meanwhile, plans to target its attack on
Mori's "divine nation" remark that sparked an uproar and dragged
down Mori's support ratings.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to question the process of the transfer of power
to Mori after his predecessor Keizo Obuchi was rushed to hospital
on April 2 due to a stroke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
