<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia to Expand Organic Farming, Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region has decided to develop organic farming and
tourism to make optimal use of its natural resources and protect
the environment.
</P>
<P>
The regional government recently issued a circular, calling on
all local governments to nurture the two sectors as new growth
factors in their economies and a means to better protect the
environment. The region aims to have 800,000 ha of farmland for
organic food production by the year 2005, to account for one third
of its food output.
</P>
<P>
The region will strive to make rational use of underground
water, reduce the use of plastic film, pesticides and chemical
fertilizer, and control industrial pollution, according to the
circular.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia, with 1.183 million sq km of land, has the
largest grassland and forest resources among all provincial
administrations in China, which amount to 87 million hectares and
32 million hectares, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia is known for its animal husbandry, but excessive
grazing over the years has resulted in deterioration of the
environment. The regional government therefore decided that animal
farming should be kept at a rational scale, while diversified
undertakings should be developed to improve its economic structure.
</P>
<P>
Since the region initiated a project to develop the organic
food industry in 1992, a total of 78 such businesses have emerged,
making over 170 kinds of organic food products including mutton,
beef, milk, processed edible herb, according to the latest
statistics from the organic food development center in Inner
Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia also plans to invest more than 50 million yuan
to upgrade the tourism facilities in two of its major grasslands
Holonbuyr and Xilin Gol to develop them into major tourist
attractions in the region.
</P>
<P>
A tourism development fund is also expected to be established
in the region to provide support for the tourism sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
