<HEADLINE> More Chinese Children Surging Into Cyberage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Chinese
children are quietly sailing into the cyberage through the
Internet, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the Beijing-based China Mainland Marketing
Research Company indicated that 67 percent of urban children
surveyed can use computers and over 17 percent know how to log on
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The survey was targeted at the 4.5 million children between the
ages of six and 15 in nine major cities across China. Some 2,700
samples were collected.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that nearly 43 percent of the children
surveyed who surf the net log on to browse for information.
</P>
<P>
However, even more kids, 48 percent of the 17 percent able to
use the Internet, like to visit chatrooms.
</P>
<P>
Video games were the third largest attraction on the Internet,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Many schools in Chinese cities have already offered their
students computer courses. And the number of families with their
own computers has been increasing rapidly in China.
</P>
<P>
Some 28 percent of the children surveyed have computers at home,
the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
