<HEADLINE> Fijian Chiefs to Decide Political Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's Great Council of Chiefs is
to have a meeting Friday to decide the country's immediate
political future.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press quoted a Fijian army spokesman
as saying that it had been agreed with coup leader George Speight
that the chiefs decide whether Fiji should meet Speight's demands
for an interim civilian government or the army's preferred option
of a continuing interim military regime.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements are being made to bring about 50 chiefs into Suva
from outlying regions.
</P>
<P>
"The chiefs' decision will be final," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
As far as the hostages are concerned, the spokesman said they
would be released and it was just a question of when.
</P>
<P>
The former Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and 30 other
hostages have been held in the parliamentary complex since May 19.
Hostage-taker George Speight insisted that himself and his gunmen
should play an influential role in the future political structure
after taking so much risk.
</P>
<P>
The Great Council of Chiefs has been formally approved by the
1997 constitution and it's chairman is the former Prime Minister
Sitiveni Rabuka.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the military and Speight are expected to
resume later Friday to tie up the final details of the deal.
</P>
