<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Wahid Officiates Aceh Cease-fire Amid Explosions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid officiated the cease-fire between the Indonesian Military (
TNI) and the Free Aceh Movement (GAM), just hours after a dozen
explosions rocked Aceh on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address on Thursday night, the president said
the humanitarian pause accord would be "the beginning of a new era
of peace" for the people of Aceh after decades of civil strife.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there will be peace in Aceh and peace will bring
prosperity to the region," the president was quoted by the
Indonesian Observer Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wahid promised greater autonomy for Aceh, a province with
special autonomous status in northwestern Sumatra, but ruled out
rebel demands for full independence.
</P>
<P>
He said that Aceh's people would enjoy "a good future and
prosperity" by remaining part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The president delivered the speech to welcome the
implementation of the humanitarian pause accord starting June 2.
The three-month accord was signed in Geneva, Switzerland, on May
12.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the accord, a joint panel of rebel leaders,
government officials and independent Swiss mediators will oversee
the deal in Aceh. It would regularly report to another "joint
forum" based in Switzerland, which is the highest decision-making
body. The goal would be to extend the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, home-made bomb explosions
and gunfire rocked the provincial capital of Banda Aceh and Aceh
Besar district, about 60 kilometers south of Banda Aceh. The
powerful explosions and gunfire, which started at 11 p.m. local
time on Wednesday and lasted until 03:00 a.m. on Thursday, had
made the people afraid to carry out their daily activities.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency quoted a source as saying that after the
huge explosions, people continued to hear gunfire for almost 60
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Aceh Besar police chief Lt. Col. Sayed Husaini admitted that
the explosions had shaken Banda Aceh city and its surroundings.
</P>
<P>
"Security officers have checked several locations where the
explosions occurred. But no casualties or material damage were
found," Husaini was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
Local residents expressed hope that Thursday's happening would
be the last instance of violence prior to the implementation of
the accord.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the incident will be the last to happen. We want to
live in peace. We hope the conflicts can be ended immediately," a
young woman told Antara.
</P>
<P>
Violence between government security forces and armed GAM
rebels killed more than 400 persons this year. Twenty-three of the
fatalities occurred after the signing of the accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
