<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. Small Businesses Going Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Several surveys released this
week by U.S. market research firms have found small business
owners in the United States are increasingly taking their
businesses online and purchasing online.
</P>
<P>
An annual survey conducted by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet (D&AMP;B) in
February and March of 2000 found that 40 percent of the small
businesses have their own Web sites, up from just over a quarter
last year, and that 70 percent now have Internet access.
</P>
<P>
The survey found 38 percent of the U.S. small companies with
Web sites transacted business with customers over their sites. On
average, 8 percent of 1999 revenues came from their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
D&AMP;B also found a notable change in the way small businesses use
the Internet. The top use of the Internet among small businesses
is e-mail, with 71 percent of them saying so. Forty-three percent
said they used the Web for purchasing goods and services for the
business. Use of the Internet for research at work dropped, from
71 percent in 1998 to 58 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Small businesses owned by women were more likely to have
Internet access than their male-owned counterparts, the survey
found. They were also more likely to conduct research and to
purchase goods and services on the Web.
</P>
<P>
A survey by PSI Global found small businesses of all sizes have
quickly embraced the Internet as a new information channel. Two-
thirds of U.S. small businesses are online, and 30 percent of them
have a Web site, according to the PSI survey of 876 businesses
with annual sales ranging from half a million dollars to 10
million dollars. Eight percent of the businesses have been selling
online for about a year and predict that 15 percent of their
revenue in the year 2000 will come from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that 19 percent of small businesses use
the Internet as a communications channel for introducing products
and services to potential customers.
</P>
<P>
The third survey of more than 1,000 small firms conducted by
International Data Corporation (IDC) found e-commerce is the wave
of the future for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to IDC's research, the number of U.S. small
businesses engaged in e-commerce will increase from 400,000 in
1998 to nearly 2.8 million in 2003. Overall, most small businesses
have annual revenues less than 5 million dollars, but the average
annual revenues of companies that regard the Internet as important
are significantly higher than those that rate it less important.
Of 7.5 million small businesses, 11 percent were engaged in e-
commerce activity in 1999, IDC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Czech Republic Enter European U-21 Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy and the Czech Republic are to
face each other in the Sunday's final at the European Under 21
soccer championships after both teams claimed victories in
Bratislava of Slovakia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Italy captured the spot with a 3-1 win over Turkey to move atop
the Group B standings. The Czechs gained first place in Group A
with a 4-2 win over Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia's 2-0 win over England left them tied with Italy.
Despite identical records, the Italians moved on to the
championship game on goal differential.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia will play the Netherlands in a third-place game Sunday.
