<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Clinton Open "Modern Government" Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
and visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton began a meeting here
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
With middle-left government heads from 12 other states, the
two were trying to draw up a blueprint for "good governance" in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Over a dinner Friday evening in the Charllottenburg palace,
Berlin, the leaders began talks about the modernization of social
welfare system, and the new missions of the government in
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Argentina, Brasilia, Chile, and South Africa --
Fernando de la Rua, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, Ricardo Lagos
Escobar, and Thabo Mbeki -- participated in the conference.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the meeting were the government chiefs of
Canada, France, Greece, Italy, New Zealand, the Netherlands,
Portugal and Sweden: Jean Cretien, Lionel Jospin, Costas Simitis,
Giuliano Amato, Helen Clark, Wim Kok, Antonio Guterres and Goran
Persson.
</P>
<P>
The conference followed "the third-way summit" last year in
Florence, Italy.
</P>
<P>
A draft declaration said the leaders would agree on the
government's role in stabilizing financial markets and necessary
measures to keep social justice in the globalization.
</P>
<P>
The draft also said the Internet-led New Economy would bring
the world "unprecedented wealth." A final statement is due to be
published Saturday after their formal talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 200 scientists and government advisors from
the 14 countries held another meeting in so-called "working groups.
"
</P>
<P>
Invited by Schroeder, the experts were trying to find ideas
for leaders on the social system, education, the Internet and the
New Economy.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said they had agreed on the key of education in the
21st century and called for a radical liberalization of the
education system.
</P>
<P>
"In the future we will distinguish people as those well-
educated and bad-educated," said Georges Charpak, a 1992 Nobel
Physical Prize laureate who led a working group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Authority Evaluates Cost of Improvements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is what ACP general secretary Leon Gonzalez said Friday
here, stating that a third set of floodgates could be an alternate
solution to the widening of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez also said that the cost could amount to four billion
dollars if the construction of bridges, a hydroelectric plant, and
the concession are taken into account.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the third set of floodgates, said Gonzalez, exceeds
the
financial capability of Panama, so this must be managed at the
level of the international society as a project of international
infrastructure for the world economic development.
</P>
<P>
An office of studies of Capacity of the Canal had been created
previously, where diverse projects of expansion of the waterway
have been analyzed during two years, said Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
The number of high sea commercial ships that traverse now the
Canal every year is some 13,000 or more, an average of 35 transits
a day.
</P>
<P>
The average time of transit of the ships through the
interoceanic waterway during the same period is of more than 30
hours.
</P>
<P>
This means that the present situation of the Canal is in the
brink of saturation, because of the growing demand for the
waterway services and the increase of international trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
