<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Says Port of Djibouti Capable of Handling Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia said Friday that the
port of Djibouti is capable of handling the relief good destined
for Ethiopian drought victims.
</P>
<P>
The port now unloads 4,700 tons of relief items daily, Tadese
Bekele, senior official of the Disaster Prevention and
Preparedness Commission (DPPC) said at the weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has refused to use Eritrean port of Assab for handling
relief aid as requested by foreign donors and international aid
agencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the delivery of food aid from
central warehouses to the distribution centers is also going
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
About 3,200 tons of goods are distributed every day to various
 locations throughout Ethiopia from the central warehouses in
Makale, Kombolcha, Nazreth and Dire Dawa, Belete said
</P>
<P>
More than eight million Ethiopians were reportedly facing with
starvation following long spells of drought. About 800,000 tons of
food are required to feed them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
