<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Probes Human Rights Abuses in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The UN mission in Sierra Leone has
launched an investigation into human rights abuses by the
country's fighting parties, an official of the mission said Friday
in the country's capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted Richard Bernett, head of the
mission's human rights section as saying that the probe is
intended to get a " complete picture" of the human rights
situation in the war- torn west African nation.
</P>
<P>
He said human rights investigations have been undertaken in
places in the country like Freetown, Waterloo, Masiaka, Port Loko,
Lungi, Bo and Rogbere junction for over three weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, Bernett said that access to other areas outside
Freetown has been limited since the recent outbreak of
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the current fighting there are reports of
civilians being subjected to forced labor, abduction, rape, and
physical harassment.
</P>
<P>
Fear of gross human rights violations has caused thousands of
civilians to flee from areas controlled or attacked by the
Revolutionary United Front rebels, deteriorating the humanitarian
problems.
</P>
<P>
Bernett said the UN mission was concerned about the situation
of the war prisoners, thousands of abducted civilians, taken over
in recent years by the rebels, and that of the rebel child
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He added that the mission has also received reports indicating
that government and its allied forces have been responsible for
extra-judicial executions, arbitrary detention and beatings.
</P>
<P>
The allied forces of the Sierra Leone army include the Civil
Defence Force, known as 'Kamajors' and members of the ousted
military junta headed by Johnny Koroma, under the banner of the
Armed Forces Revolutionary Council.
</P>
<P>
Bennett said reports from the investigations would be forwarded
to the UN Secretary General's special representative in Sierra
Leone and to the UN High Commission on Human Rights in Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
