<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Energy Industry to Face Personnel Crunch, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More than one million employees
have been shed by the largest 25 U.S. oil companies since 1982 as
a result of consolidation, divestiture and downsizing, according
to a new study released this week.
</P>
<P>
This frenzy could leave the industry critically short of
skilled professionals, according to the comprehensive study of U.S.
oil industry employment by John S. Herold, Inc., a U.S. research
and consulting firm exclusively on the petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 25 years of strong economic expansion that have
witnessed the creation of a net 20 million new jobs in the United
States, Herold said that large energy companies eliminated nearly
one-third of the workforce that existed in 1974. From the peak of
1.65 million employees of the top public oils in 1982, the 1999
employee count of roughly 640,000 workers is down 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
On average, the largest oil companies have shed an astonishing
5.2 percent of their workforce every year for the past dozen years.
The 10 largest oil companies again axed more than 38,000 workers
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Herold's analysis confirmed that downsizing can generate
positive results for the large oils, as evidenced by average
growth in pre-tax cash flow per employee of five percent over the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
"With crude oil and natural gas pricing and demand fundamentals
extremely solid today, energy sector employment should be
expanding," said the firm. "However, personnel reduction programs
instituted during the oil price meltdown of 1998-1999 and
resulting from consolidation among the large oils continue to '
downsizing momentum' that is inconsistent with today's upbeat
energy market."
</P>
<P>
Employment in the oil and natural gas sector is projected to
decline six percent between 1998 and 2008.
</P>
<P>
Herold found that energy industry distress, coupled with the
inability to attract young talent, have contributed to a
pronounced "graying of the energy workforce" from the drilling rig
to the boardroom. More than 65 percent of workers in the oil and
gas industry are between 35 and 54.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, recent trends suggest that a personnel shortage in
oilfield service is already becoming evident, Herold said. The
dearth of experienced personnel is much more of an issue today
than equipment availability.
</P>
<P>
Herold said that the oil industry may have a difficult time
overcoming its tarnished image. At best, the firm said, the energy
industry is tarred with being a mature, low-growth, "old economy"
sector, making it unattractive to bright new talent. At worse,
energy companies can be charged with brutal and short-sighted
treatment of their people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxembourg Police Criticized for Ruse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Luxembourg police were criticized
Friday for posing as television camera crew to lure and shot a
gunman holding more than two dozen children hostage.
</P>
<P>
The Brussels-based International Federation of Journalists, the
world's largest journalists' organization, chided Luxembourg
police for posing as journalists to lure the 39-year-old gunman
into an ambush and ending a hostage crisis at a day-care center at
Wasserbillig bordering Germany.
</P>
<P>
The federation asked for an investigation into the police
tactics.
</P>
<P>
When the gunman, said to have a history of mental problems,
emerged for an "interview" late Thursday holding a child in one
arm and a hand grenade in the other, police shot him twice in the
head to overwhelm him.
</P>
<P>
The police ambush ended the 28-hour hostage crisis that started
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Aidan White, general secretary of the International Federation
of Journalists, said in a written statement that the police
tactics were disturbing in that television cameramen are always
potential targets when filming in dangerous situations.
</P>
<P>
"Incidents like this may put them even more at risk from
trigger-happy criminals," the general secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Hostage-taker Neji Bejaoui, an unemployed Tunisian immigrant,
walked into the Wasserbillig nursery school with a pistol, a hand
grenade and a knife and took 49 children and three teachers
hostage.
</P>
<P>
Bejaoui was recovering from his injuries Friday after surgery
and police said that his wounds were no longer life threatening.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker said that police
were forced to act when the gunman demanded fleeing in a car with
three children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
