<HEADLINE> Rains Cause 1,000 Victims in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Strong and unusual rains fell for
several hours in the Second Chilean Region (Antofagasta) and
caused almost 1,000 victims, cut roads, isolated communities,
paralyzed work in the mines and closed two border ports.
</P>
<P>
The uninterrupted rains started Thursday night and continued
until Friday morning. The bad weather front left 540 victims in
the last hours just in Antofagasta because of the state of the
roofs of their houses.
</P>
<P>
Emergencies regional director Hernan Flores said Friday that
the rains caused collapses on the road that links Calama with San
Pedro de Atacama, and that the traffic in that route is
interrupted.
</P>
<P>
The great amount of snow that fell on the northern mountain
range forced the authorities to close the Jama and Sico border
ports.
</P>
<P>
The strong rain, hailstorms, fog, and strong wind forced the
suspension of scientific work in the most powerful astronomical
observatory of the world, located 2,632 meters above sea level in
the Paranal Mountain. The domes were closed to prevent damage to
the giant mirrors.
</P>
<P>
The main mining firms of the zone decided to stop some of the
operations for safety sake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
