<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise In Second Consecutive Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose strongly
in the second consecutive session Friday as additional signs
showed a slowdown in the pace of U.S. economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 142.56 or 1.3
percent at 10,794.76, extending its gain of 129.87 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 230.88 or 6.4
percent at 3,813.38. The composite ended the week with a gain of
608.27 points or 18.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 28.45 at 1,477.26.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose after the Labor Department reported that the
unemployment rate climbed back to 4.1 percent in May from a 30-
year low of 3.9 percent in April. American businesses cut 116,000
jobs in the month under pressure of interest rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department also said average hourly earnings for
labor force rose just 0.1 percent in May, a sharp decline from a 0.
4 percent increase in April.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the report on weak jobs and lower earnings, the
Commerce Department reported that orders to American factories
fell by 4.3 percent in April, the biggest decline since November
1990.
</P>
<P>
The two separate reports showed additional signs that the
tightening monetary policy by the Federal Reserve is working. The
Federal Reserve has raised interest rate six times since last June
in an effort to cool off the U.S. economy and keep inflation at
bay.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street analysts believe that the slowdown in the economy
would lead the Federal Reserve to end the tightening cycle after
one more rate hike or two. The optimism encouraged investors to
move in the market to pick up stocks they had abandoned amid fears
of rising rates.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 8.23 at 659.69 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 10.97 at 923.32. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 20.57 at 513.03.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,218 up, 854 down and 349
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.15 billion shares from 951.19
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
