<DOCNO> XIE20000602.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researcher Backs Lockerbie Prosecution Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, the Netherlands, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A British
researcher Friday backed the prosecution's case against two
Libyans by testifying that the bomb that brought down Pan Am
Flight 103 was some way away from the fuselage skin.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Peel, from the British Defense Evaluation and
Research Agency, calculated that a 450-gram explosive device was
hidden 24 inches (60.9 centimeters) from the aircraft wall.
</P>
<P>
His calculation had a margin of error of four inches (10
centimeters) either way, he added.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyer Richard Keen pointed out differences in the two
reports both prepared by Peel about the Lockerbie bombing, the
first being written shortly after the crash on December 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Peel defended the second report, saying that it was based on an
improved analytical model as well as results of tests on
explosions in aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The exact location of the bomb that brought down the New York-
bound Boeing 747 jumbo, killing 259 people on board and 11 others
on the ground, is crucial to the prosecution's case that accused
Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa Fahima of hiding
plastic explosives in a cassette player which was then hidden in a
suitcase that was put in a cargo container.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Protheroe, an expert from Britain's Air Accident
Investigation Branch, testified last week that his agency made a
mistake in calculating the distance between the planted bomb and
the aircraft wall.
</P>
<P>
If calculated by using the "mach stem" formula, he said, the
distance would be around 12 inches (30.4 centimeters) instead of
25 inches (63.5 centimeters).
</P>
<P>
Peel, however, said that the mach stem theory was developed to
measure the damage done by a nuclear bomb exploded in mid-air and
that the theory did not apply to explosions within aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
