<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel Group to Expropriate Corrupt Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia (FARC) announced Friday a new "law" to stop
administrative corruption that will oblige those responsible to
return with interests and fines illicitly appropriated money, and
even the expropriation of their assets.
</P>
<P>
FARC spokesman Raul Reyes said in a telephone communication
that "law 003 goes in force today."
</P>
<P>
The FARC had announced before this rule on administrative
corruption another on the agrarian reform, which it has not issued
yet, and one more that forces Colombians with more than one
million dollars to deliver them 10 percent of their assets.
</P>
<P>
The rebels pretend with this new decision to warn those who
have appropriated in an illicit way public assets that they must
return them in full together with the corresponding interests,
according to the current banking rate of interest.
</P>
<P>
The FARC is the oldest and largest rebel group in the South
American country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
